<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-23 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, PA Security Heads Pledge Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite mounting tension
between Israel and the Palestinian Authority (PA), security
heads from both sides today reached agreement on increasing
cooperation in fighting against "terror."
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made in Jerusalem, where Israeli Public Security
Minister Avigdor Kahalani held his first meeting with PA security
head Jibril Rajoub. Kahalani described the meeting as successful,
saying the two sides had pledged to increase cooperation in
combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The two men agreed to set up a line of communication on
combating terrorism following the Friday suicide bombing in a
Tel Aviv cafe, which killed 4 people and wounded dozens of
others.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub promised he would take all necessary measures to
prevent more bombing attacks against Israel in order to
enable the continuation of the peace process. He also warned
Israel against suspending peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"Co-existence and peace is the only way and the only
option that we have. The Palestinian police and the
(Palestinian) authority would take all necessary measures to
enable the leaders of both sides to continue the peace
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel blamed the PA for being responsible for the Tel
Aviv bombing by giving the green-light for "terrorist attacks" to
militant Palestinian organizations such as Hamas, which claimed
responsibility for the Friday bombing in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli officials and security experts acknowledged
that the cooperation from the Palestinian security forces was
essential for a success in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Also today, senior Israeli army officers also held talks
with Palestinian police officials in an attempt to increase
coordination in preventing the infiltration of potential
Palestinian militants. Israel is maintaining a total closure on
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The whole Jewish state was keeping high security alert
amid intelligence warnings of more bombing attacks. Road blocks
and checkpoints were set up in main entrances to major
cities, while additional security forces were deployed in city
centers to deter possible attackers.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of current tension, Israeli border guards opened
fire at a Palestinian car in a Jerusalem suburb checkpoint,
wounding two Palestinians who tried to flee from the
security checks.
</P>
<P>
Yair Yitzhak, Jerusalem police chief, warned today suicide
bombings could also take place in Jerusalem and other cities
alike. Although most celebrations on the Purim holiday will be
held as scheduled today and Monday, they will be heavily
guarded as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Tel Aviv bombing was the first suicide bombing attack
since late February to early March when a series of suicide
bombings killed over 60 people in major cities of Jerusalem, Tel
Aviv and Asheklon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
