<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists at Sino-Russia Border Increased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- China and Russian Federation
exchanged a record high of some 300,000 tourists at their border
areas in 1996, latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Tourism continued to grow to over 30 percent in the first
two months of this year, authorities of Heilongjiang Province
announced.
</P>
<P>
In the past tourists from Japan, and Hong Kong and Macao made
up the bulk of the relatively small amount of overseas tourists to
this cold northernmost Chinese province. Russia has now become the
largest tourist source to Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
Provincial tourist officials attributed the increase of the
tourist exchange to the 24 ports of entry opened along the border,
and the introduction of one-day and multi-day tours offered at
border cities of the both sides.
</P>
<P>
The development of tourism has contributed to the booming of
small cities along the borders and to the swelling of local
coffers, local officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
