<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossiled Rhino Skeleton Found in Xinjiang Best in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
confirmed that the fossiled skeleton of a giant rhino unearthed in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is the best and
most complete in the world.
</P>
<P>
The fossils, dating back 30 million years, were excavated in
1993 and fixed recently at the Beijing Museum of Natural History.
Around the fossils of the rhino, tortoise fossils were also
discovered.
</P>
<P>
The fixed skeleton is about eight to nine meters long and some
four to five meters high, and has been sent back to Turpan Museum
in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
The giant rhino used to be the largest herbivorous mammal, and
the fossils are of high value for the study of animal evolution
and environmental changes, according to experts with the Institute
of Vertebrate Paleontology under the Chinese Academy of Sciences
and the China Geological Museum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
