<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buthelezi Again Appointed as Acting S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- South African Home Affairs
Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi, who was appointed as acting
president for two days last month, once again accepted the
position today.
</P>
<P>
"It is awe inspiring to be head of state even for a couple of
days, especially as powerful a state as this one," Buthelezi told
reporters in Pretoria, the administrative capital of South Africa
after being sworn in.
</P>
<P>
He said, "it is a greater responsibility to be in charge of a
whole country, but there is really nothing new about it."
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi, a well known opponent in the cabinet, said he
appreciated the trust President Nelson Mandela had placed in him
by appointing him to the position of acting president for the
second time in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
He would hold the position from Tuesday to Thursday this week,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is reportedly due to leave for Bangladesh and India on
Monday while Deputy President Thabo Mbeki is in Zaire and is
scheduled to go to visit Angola later.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi had acted in Mandela's capacity in February while
Mandela and Mbeki attended a meeting of the World Economic Forum
in Davos, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi will go to Cape Town, the legislative capital of
South Africa on Monday, informed sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
