<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agricultural Province Absorbs Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan
province, a leading agricultural province in the country, has used
more than one billion US dollars of foreign capital to develop its
agriculture over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Most of the investment from overseas flowed to township
enterprises and hydroelectric power plants in the province,
according to local government officials.
</P>
<P>
During the period, Sichuan introduced more than 500 million US
dollars to set up some 300 large township firms with high
technical levels.
</P>
<P>
The province also used 300 million US dollars in building
Shengzhong Reservoir, Wudu Water Conservancy Project and other
major projects.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, overseas funds have gone into the farming, forestry
and animal husbandry sectors.
</P>
<P>
local government officials praised highly the influx of foreign
funds, saying that it made up the scarcity of input in agriculture
and helped introduce advanced techniques and equipment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
