<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-23 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Parliament Expresses Support to Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian parliament today
expressed its confidence in and support for the government of Prime
Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri amid wide speculations that a major
cabinet shake-up is near.
</P>
<P>
The 456-member People's Assembly, at a session under Speaker
Ahmed Fathi Sorour, endorsed the policy statement read out by
Ganzouri before the parliament on December 23.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen members of the parliament from the opposition voted
against the statement and two independents abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
Yassin Seraguddin, leader of the parliamentary mission of the
opposition Wafd Party, refused to vote for renewing confidence in
the government.
</P>
<P>
Sorour lauded the government for its savvy in the management
of crises and praised President Hosni Mubarak's "wise policy"
that has won international acclaim.
</P>
<P>
Last week, however, there were rumors from local journalists
and political pundits about a major shake-up of the cabinet,
saying that Ganzouri might change as many as 15 ministers.
</P>
<P>
local observers and politicians believe that Ganzouri, who
replaced Atef Sidki on January 2, 1995 in the last cabinet
shake-up, may want to drop those who had been already in place
when he took over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
