<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Celebrate 100-day Countdown of HK's Return (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- With great cheer and hope, people
around the country held various activities today to mark the
100-day countdown to Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Late night on March 22, hundreds of university students in
Beijing flocked to an electronic board showing the countdown east
of the Tian'anmen Square, awaiting the upcoming 100-day countdown
for Hong Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
As the moment came at midnight, the young people applauded and
cheered, "Hong Kong, come home, Hong Kong, come home," swaying
banners with uplifting slogans, and singing songs.
</P>
<P>
This morning, more than 1,000 students went to a park in
western Beijing to start a torch relay, while thousands of people
in the park signed their names on a large piece of white silk
cloth or offered a few words of blessing related to Hong Kong's
return.
</P>
<P>
In Shenzhen City, which borders Hong Kong, more than 100 buses
appeared in the street carrying large red banners that read
"Greeting Hong Kong's return, giving good service for 100 days."
And workers in the Shenzhen Airport and Luohu Customs said they
would greet Hong Kong's return with better work.
</P>
<P>
A park in Shenzhen witnessed the ground-breaking ceremony for
constructing a wall consisting of 1997 memorial bricks. People
also planted trees to mark the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Residents of Guangzhou City in south China have been viewing
Hong Kong people as their brothers and sisters, and they are
expecting to celebrate their reunion soon. Over the past few days,
work units in Guangzhou have been organizing people to study the
Basic Law of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In Nanjing, capital city of east China's Jiangsu Province, 800
senior school students went to the Jinghai Temple, where the
Treaty of Nanking had been signed 99 years ago, the result of
which Hong Kong was ceded to Britain.
</P>
<P>
The students declared their adulthood and planted pines and
cypresses, showing their determination not to forget the national
humiliation and their responsibility to revitalize the country.
</P>
<P>
A three-ton, 1.997-m-tall "wake-up bell" will be cast and
erected on June 1 in the temple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
