<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Celebrate 100-day Countdown Of HK's Return (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, the country's biggest economic center, held a
calligraphy exhibition to mark the 100-day countdown for Hong
Kong's return to her motherland. Nearly 140 well-known
calligraphers took part and expressed their feelings in their
works.
</P>
<P>
In China's north port city of Tianjin, people from all walks of
life including some 1,000 compatriots from Hong Kong and Macao
planted 1997 trees in the city's forest park to celebrate the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
A monument, 199.7 cm high and 71 cm wide, has been set up
amidst the trees to show the city's nine million residents'
anticipation for the return of Hong Kong. In addition, the city
set free 1,997 pigeons.
</P>
<P>
In northwest China's Urumqi City, the city railway bureau's
some 160,000 employees of different ethnic groups took part in
various kinds of activities to celebrate the 100-day
countdown. They performed singing and dancing in trains, children
drew paintings, and the bureau held a contest on the history and
development of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bureau asked the employees to provide the best
service to travellers, and welcome the return of Hong Kong in
their day-to-day work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
