<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Labor Remains 25.5 Points Ahead in Opinion Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The first opinion poll conducted
since Britain's general election date was announced last week
showed that the main opposition Labor Party's lead remains an
extraordinary 25.5 points.
</P>
<P>
A Gallup poll for The Sunday Telegraph, which was conducted in
the second half of last week and was released today, found that
Labor has the backing of a clear majority of voters, 54.5 percent,
while the Conservatives trail on 29 points. The Liberal Democrats
are on 10.5 points.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that this is a setback for Prime Minister John
Major, who has pinned his hopes on the belief that the imminence
of the election will concentrate voters' minds on the threat of an
incoming Labor government.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the result of the poll meant that Major's
attempt to catch Labor Party unawares and rally Conservative
support by declaring the election date early has also failed.
</P>
<P>
However, Major insisted that Tory strategy would eventually
bear fruit. The prime minister also hit out at Labor's use of
"dirty tricks" instead of fighting on the central issues of
politics and the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
