<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Marks World TB Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will mark the World
Tuberculosis (TB) Day on Monday following reports on a sharp TB
increase in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Ministry of Health and Child Welfare said
today more than 30,000 Zimbabweans died of TB in the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
The disease kills more people today than at any other time in
history, although almost all of the deaths are preventable, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said neglect, AIDS and multi-drug resistance
were the three main driving forces behind the spread of TB.
</P>
<P>
TB cases had decreased in Zimbabwe until the mid-1980s when
the first AIDS case was reported. Since 1987, there has been a
sharp increase of as much as 400 percent, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that TB will be the main killer of HIV-
positive patients by the year 2000. In general, TB is more
vicious and accelerated when associated with HIV infection and,
therefore, lead to more serious clinical symptoms in a short
time," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Three million people died of TB around the world in 1995,
surpassing the number in the worst years of the epidemic around
1900. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
