<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-23 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Destroy Home of Suicide Bomber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel is to destroy the
home of the suicide bomber who killed three Israeli women and
wounded dozens of others in a Tel Aviv cafe Friday, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomber was identified as Moussa Ranimat, 28, who lived
in the village of Kafr Tsuri near the West Bank town of Hebron,
which is still under the Israeli military control.
</P>
<P>
Ranimat, member of the Islamic militant group Hamas, had been
detained by Israeli police twice for questioning for his
suspected membership in Hamas.
</P>
<P>
He had worked in two restaurants in Rishion Lezion near Tel
Aviv illegally before launching the suicide attack in protest
against Israel's current actions to build a Jewish settlement in
Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other suicide bombers who were usually single, Ranimat
was married and a father of four children.
</P>
<P>
Demolishing homes of extremists who launched suicide attacks
against the Jewish state has been a usual practice of punishment
taken by Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to the Israeli law, the family of the suicide bomber
can appeal to the country's High Court of Justice which is
certain to reject the request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
