<HEADLINE> Cyprus Releases 2 Allegedly Involved in Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today released one Turk
and one Turkish Cypriot, who were held in alleged connection with
a case of espionage against the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Police announced that the two were released for lack of
evidence in espionage.
</P>
<P>
The released are 37-year-old Turk Mustafa Omer Konor, who was
married to a Greek Cypriot, and Turkish Cypriot Dijan Nejip, also
37, who lived with a Greek Cypriot.
</P>
<P>
Police also said the two were examined by a U.N. doctor
before being released. The doctor did not find anything wrong
with them.
</P>
<P>
However, a third person, Turkish national Nedjip Sari
Chichekli, is still in custody and is scheduled to appear
before the Assize Court Monday to face charges of espionage.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier announcement by police, Chichekli had
confessed to spying on National Guard's military positions over
the past 18 months for Turkey, in exchange for 2,500 Cyprus pounds
(about 5,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
All three, who were living in the southern coastal town of
Limassol, were arrested on March 8 and detained after police
found military documents, newspaper clippings concerning arms
acquisition program of the National guard and maps outlining army
camps.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Petros Clerides, the country's top lawer, announced
here that famous Turkish Cypriot lawyer Ali Nadal will arrive
from the Turkish-occupied northern areas to defend the three
suspects.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Attorney-General's Office will ensure
that the Republic's interests are safeguarded, so are those
of the charged.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of
short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
