<HEADLINE> Arabs to Seek Support Again at UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries will, for the
second time, resort to the United Nations to confront the
U.S. veto over the U.N. resolution barring a new Israeli
settlement plan in East Jerusalem, the Arab League (AL) chief
said today.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab group at the General Assembly is working to issue a
strong and clear resolution that would back the Arab call on
Israel to halt its settlement expansion in East Jerusalem," AL
Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The Arab leader regretted that the United States has tarnished
its role as a fair mediator in the Mideast East by using the veto
twice on the resolution that demanded Israel to stop building
6,500 housing units on Har Homa in East Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians want to make their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Following its first veto on March 7, the U.S. again rejected
an Arab-sponsored U.N. Security Council resolution Friday. In
contrast, the General Assembly, where there is no veto, approved
a similar resolution with a vote of 130-2 earlier last week.
</P>
<P>
Friday's vote coincided with a suicide bombing attack at a Tel
Aviv cafe, killing at least three people and wounding 47. The
militant Muslim group of Hamas has claimed responsibility for the
bombing in revenge of Israel's "terror of bulldozers".
</P>
<P>
"Two vetoes in two weeks also lead the Arab and Islamic world
to question the American role as a sponsor of the Middle East
peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It not only raises several question marks, but is also most
regrettable," Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. veto has encouraged Israel to further its
settlement policy, he affirmed, it will not weaken the Arab
commitment towards the strategic option of peace.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the General Assembly will help defuse violence and
counter-violence that has begun to escalate in the region and
salvage the peace process that has reached one of its most
dangerous phases," he added.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief called upon the U.S., a key sponsor of the peace
process since 1979, to exercise its influence over Israel and
save the peace march.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli policies require parties concerned,
especially the U.S., to adopt a firmer stance," Meguid told
the press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
