<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Industry Plays Greater Role in U.S. Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 23 (Xinhua) -- High technology has replaced the
traditional cyclical industries as the main driving force for
growth of the United States, according to the latest issue of the
"Business Week".
</P>
<P>
The nation's economic expansion of the 1990s has been fueled
largely by the strong growth of the information technology
industry, rather than housing and autos, it said, adding that it
is not the stock market either to determine how long this
expansion will last.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the high-tech sector has contributed
27 percent of the growth in gross domestic product, compared with
14 percent for residential housing and only 4 percent for
residential housing and only 4 percent for the auto sector.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, it said, a stunning 33 percent of GDP
growth has come from information-technology industries, propelled
by things ranging from the Internet boom to the rise of
direct-broadcast satellite television.
</P>
<P>
There is a new business cycle in the country, which is tied to
the health of the high-tech sector, it said.
</P>
<P>
The computer, software, and communications industries have
grown at a pace far exceeding the rest of the economy over the
past three years, helping to extend the expansion.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech's contribution to the country's GDP totaled 420
billion U.S. dollars in 1996, up 15 percent from 1995. The pace
was much faster than the 2.5 percent increase of GDP.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, with high tech having grown so big, the
economy is now vulnerable to a high-tech slowdown in a way that
was never true before.
</P>
<P>
It indicated that there are already troubling signs of weakness
in those industries that, if prolonged, could foreshadow a wider
slump -- as well as a steep decline in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The magazine also advised the country's policy makers to turn
their attention to the new trend to avoid policy mistakes. It
warned that an economy is "vulnerable to a downturn when one
sector or industry expands too fast."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
