<HEADLINE> Germany, Saudi Arabia to Boost Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 23 (Xinhua) -- German Minister of
Economics Guenter Rexrodt said today that Germany and the
European Union countries were keen to boost economic ties with
Saudi Arabia and other Gulf Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Rexrodt was telling a press conference in Saudi capital
city of Riyadh after wrapping up his tow-day visit to Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that economic cooperation between the European
Union countries and Gulf Cooperation Council states could be
further enhanced once a joint GCC free trade zone is established.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on unification of the customs tariffs which
would set the stage for the establishment of the free trade
zone is still underway among the GCC states because of
difficulties over an agreement of goods classification.
</P>
<P>
The GCC is a political and economic alliance formed by
regional states of Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates,
Qatar, Oman, Kuwait and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Rexrodt arrived in Saudi Arabia Saturday to attend the 12th
meeting of the German-Saudi joint commission on economic and
technical cooperation. During the meeting, both sides discussed
the important role played by the commission.
</P>
<P>
He praised results of his talks with the Saudi officials
which he said would push forward the joint economic
cooperation, pointing out that great opportunities are awaiting
German investors in the Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
But he said "the legal and administrative structure in
Saudi Arabia are not always clear enough for foreign
investors, and the need to find a sponsor in Saudi Arabia
discourages some investors."
</P>
<P>
Oil giant Saudi Arabia said earlier this month it was
taking measures to encourage foreign investment and it was
also reviewing its foreign capital law to introduce more
incentives to international investors.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia will implement steps to provide protection of
foreign investment and ease bureaucratic obstacles in the
licensing of foreign projects.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is German's main trading partner in the Arab
world. Rexrodt asserted his country's support to Saudi efforts
in joining the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
According to figures of German embassy in Saudi Arabia,
total bilateral trade between the two countries was 4.8
billion marks (2.8 billion U.S. dollars) in Saudi Arabia's
favor in 1995, in the first nine months of 1996, it stood
at 3.7 billion marks (about 2.16 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
