<HEADLINE> Israel Urges PA to Fight Extremism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel today demanded the
Palestinian Authority (PA) to fight extremism and violence "as a
necessary stage in advancing the political process."
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Ministerial Committee for National
Security Issues, which met today, urged the Palestinians to
"prevent incitement and hostile propaganda against Israel."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu convened a meeting of
the committee today, two days after Friday's suicide bombing
attack in Tel Aviv. Confrontations ensued between Israeli
soldiers and Palestinians protesters in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Moussa Ranimat, 28, of Kafr Tsurif near Hebron of
the West Bank, detonated a three-kilogram-TNT bomb packed with
nails and pieces of metal in a coffee shop in the center of Tel
Aviv, killing three Israeli women and wounding 48 others.
</P>
<P>
A closure was imposed on the West Bank and Gaza Strip
immediately following the attack, and the home of Ranimat, a
member of Hamas for the past two years, was sealed.
</P>
<P>
Hamas claimed responsibility for the blast in a phone call to
Israel Television Channel 1 afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Israeli General Security Service chief Ami Ayalon met on
Friday night with PNA security heads and demanded they
immediately rearrest some 150 security prisoners released by the
PNA over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani blasted PNA
President Yasser Arafat for giving the green light to extremist
organizations and for failing to prevent attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of Palestinians rushed to the area between
Palestinian and Israeli-controlled Hebron in three separate
clashes Friday and Saturday, leaving dozens of Palestinians and
several Israelis wounded.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said that soldiers fired some live bullets
when "their lives were in danger," adding that 12 soldiers and
border policemen as well as an Israeli boy were slightly wounded
in the two days of confrontations.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the committee was briefed on "how
the PNA led the terrorist organizations to understand that they
had the 'green-light' to commit terrorist attacks."
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the committee also asked the Palestinians to
"process requests for the transfer of terrorists in accordance
with the interim agreement," known as the Oslo II accord, "and
to gather illegal weapons." 
</P>
</TEXT>
