<HEADLINE> UN Continues Backing Angola's Peace Process: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The international community will
continue its support for Angola's peace process until the country
achieves lasting peace, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a mass rally in the central city of Kuito, Annan
pledged that the international community, especially the U. N.,
would continue to provide assistance of all kinds to Angola until
it realizes national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief today toured Kuito in central Angola to
acquaint himself with the peace process and the difficulties
suffered by the local people in one of the cities which had been
hit hardest during the civil war.
</P>
<P>
When civil war erupted again in 1993, fierce battles were
fought in Kuito, destroying nearly all the buildings and taking
the tolls of about 50,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he was shocked to learn so many were maimed for
life and determined to contribute to ending the production and
sales of land mines in the world.
</P>
<P>
Some 150,000 people braved the rains to meet the U.N. Chief
and listen to his address at the Independence Square in the city.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains compelled Annan to cancel his trip to Huanbo, and
to Bailundo, headquarters of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) to meet its leader Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here on Saturday for a four-day visit from
Namibia. It is the third leg of his African tour. Before Namibia,
he toured South Africa. And after his stay in Angola, he will go
to Togo to attend a special OAU summit on the Zaire crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
