<HEADLINE> Turkey Appeals for Stronger German Support of Its EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- One day before German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel starts on a three-day visit to Ankara,
Turkey's ambassador to Germany today called for stronger German
support for its bid for European Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
Turkey feels it is not being treated fairly by the European
countries, said Ambassador Volkan Vural in an interview with the
German newspaper Bild (Monday issue). He added that his country
views itself as European in its history, geography and values.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Turkey has only the demand to enjoy the
same treatment as other candidates for EU membership. "It is an
injustice to deny its rights to join the EU or exclude it."
</P>
<P>
"We expect a more active support from Germany. The existing
special relationship with Germany is a factor which enhances these
expectations" he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kinkel reportedly said in Brussels today that the
Turkish demand for EU membership could not be met in the
foreseeable future given its current economic situation and human
rights problems.
</P>
<P>
According to the German Foreign Ministry, Kinkel is scheduled
to visit Turkey on March 25-27. Turkey's relations with the EU
will be the main topic when he meets with Turkey's Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller. 
</P>
