<HEADLINE> Russia, China to Sign Political, Economic Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia and China will sign
important political and economic agreements at the Sino-Russian
summit scheduled for next month, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Grigory Karasin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Karasin made the remarks before Chinese Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen's arrival in Moscow on a four-day visit to prepare for the
meeting between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, the Itar-TASS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Qian, who left Beijing for Moscow today, is
expected to meet Yeltsin, hold talks with Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Karasin said the talks between Qian, also Chinese vice premier,
and Primakov would be an "important landmark" in Russian-Chinese
relations, which he described as "surprisingly active and
comprehensive" in recent years.
</P>
<P>
On the reduction of armed forces in the border areas between
the two countries, Karasin said an agreement on this was to be
signed in April by the leaders of Russia, China, Kazakhstan,
Kirghizia and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
China became the fifth largest trading partner of Russia last
year, after Ukraine, Germany, the United States and Belarus,
reports said. 
