<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Teacher of Arabic Enchanted by Arab Dancing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Wang Lan, a young Chinese lady
holding a doctor's degree of Arabic at a university in Beijing,
has dedicated herself to Arab dancing, in her spare time.
</P>
<P>
Wang, 31, teaches in the Arabic Department of the Beijing
University of Foreign Languages, but she is better known for
studying, performing and teaching Arab dancing.
</P>
<P>
In her middle school years, Wang studied Chinese folk dancing
at a song and dance ensemble for four years in southwest China's
Yunnan Province, acquiring solid dancing skills.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, she enrolled at the university in Beijing to study
Arabic, getting the chance to acquaint herself with Arab culture,
and became enchanted by Arab dancing.
</P>
<P>
"At first, I could only learn Arab dancing with the help of
video tapes, for there were few professional persons or special
institutions in China studying Arab folk arts," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, she went to Cairo University to complete her doctor's
thesis in Arabic. In her spare time, she would go to another
university to systematically study Arab dancing. Her dancing
skills were raised to a new level.
</P>
<P>
When an Egyptian educational delegation was visiting China in
1995, Wang Lan orchestrated an evening party called "Wind from
Egypt", which was composed of short drama, dancing, poem recitation,
calligraphy, and chorus with a strong Arab flavor.
</P>
<P>
Her beautiful dance "Egypt in Dream" depicted a modern people's
reminiscence about ancient Egypt and won admiration from the
delegation members.
</P>
<P>
Hussain Kamel Bahaeddin, former Egyptian minister of education,
was quoted as saying that "the day at the (Beijing) university was
the happiest day during my stay in China."
</P>
<P>
In December, 1996, she won praise from the Chinese Ministry of
Culture for directing one Egyptian dance -- "Banana-plucking
Dance", which blended the Egyptian belt dance, club dance, and
courting dance.
</P>
<P>
At present, Wang Lan has indeed become a specialist in Arab
dancing. While lecturing on Arabic, she is also immersed in
teaching and performing Arab dancing, and occasionally
contributing articles to magazines on dancing.
</P>
<P>
However, she is not satisfied. "In addition to the study of
Arab dancing, I will introduce China's splendid folk culture to
Arabian people and enhance the understanding of the people of
China and the Arab world," Wang Lan said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
