<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Rules out Cutbacks in U.S. Troops in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- United States Vice President Al
Gore, together with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto,
today ruled out the possibility of any cutbacks in U.S. military
presence in Japan and the rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
During his 24 hours in Japan, part of an Asian tour that also
includes China and South Korea, Gore made clear that Washington
did not want changes in troop levels in Japan.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after his one-hour meeting with Hashimoto
that his country would continue to maintain present troop levels
in East Asia, and reiterated the U.S. "commitment to Japan's
security and regional stability."
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said Japan must fulfill its obligations under the
Japan-U.S. security treaty to provide facilities for the American
military, on a smooth and stable basis as long as the bilateral
relationship lasted.
</P>
<P>
"It is our responsibility to provide land and facilities (to
the U.S. military) in a stable and smooth manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the day of Gore's arrival, Hashimoto announced that
he planned to push through parliament a new law to seek continued
leases on private land used by U.S. bases on Okinawa, which are
due to expire May 14.
</P>
<P>
Anger against American forces in Okinawa boiled over after a
12-year-old girl was raped by three U.S. servicemen in September
1995.
</P>
<P>
An agreement has been reached on moving some U.S. facilities
out of Okinawa, but the island will continue to house more than
half of the 47,000 U.S. military personnel based in Japan, even
though it makes up only one percent of Japan's land mass.
</P>
<P>
The United States at present has about 100,000 troops in East
Asia, including Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
