<HEADLINE> PNA Denies Accusation of Organizing Terror </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security head
Jibril Rajoub denied today Israel's accusations that the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) had given green-light to
terrorist attacks and even organized riots.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub was commenting on the claim issued by Israeli army
intelligence chief Moshe Yaalon at a new conference Sunday
night that Rajoub had played a double game in dealing with
Israel on fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon was referring to the meeting held between Rajoub and
Israeli Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani earlier Sunday,
during which the two pledged to increase security cooperation
in fighting terror and preventing more violence.
</P>
<P>
He said that, on the other hand, Rajoub had organized the
Palestinian riots in the West Bank town of Hebron in the
past days, in which over 100 people were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub said Yaalon was apparently using the accusations to
cover his failure to prevent violence. He flatly denied his
personal involvement in the current violence. In the past days,
Palestinian police in fact have been trying hard to prevent
protesters from clashing with armed Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected the repeated claims by Israeli government
officials that PNA President Yasser Arafat had given the
green-light to extremist groups such as Hamas and Islamic
Jihad to launch terror attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for last Friday's suicide
bombing in central Tel Aviv, which killed four people and
wounded dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
With the war of words escalating, tension remained high
today with Palestinian youths battled with Israeli soldiers for
the fourth day in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers had to evacuate Jewish prayers inside the
holy Rachel's Tomb in the West Bank city of Bethlehem after
hundreds of Palestinian protesters threw stones and petrol bombs
into the barbed compound.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic clashes also broke out in Gaza and the West Bank
city of Jericho, where Israeli soldiers fired tear gas and
rubber bullets to disperse the stone-throwing Palestinian youths.
But no major casualties resulted in the clashes as Palestinian
police worked hard to prevent the protesters from charging
forward against the Israeli soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
