<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reduce TB Incidence Rate Drastically by Year 2000 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TB control experts agreed that China, having one fourth of TB
patients in the world, would also have the danger of TB epidemic
if proper steps are not taken immediately.
</P>
<P>
China has reported six million TB patients, including 1.5
million pulmonary TB patients who can infect others. Incidence
rate in rural areas two times that in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
However, health officials said about half of China's counties
and population have not benefited from proper TB curing methods,
and local medics lack both funds and knowledge in battles against
the infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health will strengthen the work of registration
in order to discover new TB patients as soon as possible, building
a complete national network for TB control, and training more
local medics, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He urged governments at all levels to allocate special funds to
support TB prevention and control work.
</P>
<P>
China has kicked off the world's biggest TB control project
since 1992, which was aided by the World Bank loans and covered a
population of 560 million in 12 provinces and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The project, adopting DOTS or "directly observed treatment,
short course" which was introduced by WHO as the only way to
reduce the transmission of TB, has helped cure 92 percent of
pulmonary TB patients.
</P>
<P>
Impressed by the success of the TB control program, the WHO
director general, Haroshi Nakajima, wrote to Premier Li Peng in
1995, hailing China's progress as a model for the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
