<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reduce TB Incidence Rate Drastically by Year 2000 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China plans to control the
incidence rate of infectious pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) below
seven persons per 10,000 persons by the year 2000, a drop of 50
percent from 1990's figure.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the average cure rate of pulmonary TB patients will
be raised to 85 percent to meet a 2000-year goal set by the World
Health Organization (WHO), according to Minister of Health Chen
Minzhang.
</P>
<P>
That means, in the next four years, the number of pulmonary TB
patients in China will drop to some 840,000 from 1.5 million at
present.
</P>
<P>
"Considering that 10 to 15 additional people can be infected by
each patient annually, we may expect China to contribute greatly
to the worldwide battle against TB disease," said Prof. Zhang
Lixing, director of the Beijing International Institute for
Tuberculosis and Lung Health.
</P>
<P>
Both the health minister and Prof. Zhang attended a seminar
held here today on the occasion of the World TB Day, which was
launched by the WHO last year not only to mark the announcement by
Dr. Robert Koch in 1882 of the discovery of the bacillus which
causes TB, but also to warn people of the new global epidemic of
TB.
</P>
<P>
"Closely linked with the emergence of multi-drug resistant
strains of TB and the HIV/AIDS epidemic, TB has re-emerged as a
major public health problem in both developed and developing
countries," A.H.Schnur, acting representative of WHO's Beijing
Office, said at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
"This situation led to WHO declaring TB a global health
emergency in April 1993," he said.
</P>
<P>
Breakdowns published by WHO showed that among 1.7 billion
people who have been infected by TB, 20 million have developed
into TB patients, and about 3.5 million of them die every year.
</P>
<P>
The organization also predicted that in the coming decade
another 90 million people will possibly become TB patients and
more than 30 million possibly be killed by the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
