<HEADLINE> S.Africa to Tighten VIP Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The South African Police
Services (SAPS) has been instructed by Safety and Security Minister
Sydney Mufamadi to tighten protection services for cabinet ministers
following recent burglaries on their houses, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi has undertaken to ensure the reorganisation of the SAPS's
VIP Protection Unit and increased security around ministers and their
homes, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The measures followed latest burglay on Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki's residence at the government's exclusive Groote Schuur
Estate in Cape Town last Wednesday, in which a music system and a
camera were stolen.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki was out of the country on official business when the theft
was spotted. No forced entry was apparent during the incident.
</P>
<P>
During the past few weeks, a string of thefts from the residences
of ministers at the heavily-guarded Groote Schuur Estate had been
reported during the ministers' absence.
</P>
<P>
Among other goods, police recovered a gold watch belonging to
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel, a leather jacket of Correctional
Services Minister Sipo Mzimela and a clock radio belonging to Defence
Minister Joe Modise.
</P>
<P>
A break-in was also reported at President Nelson Mandela's Houghton
home in Johannesburg last year.
</P>
<P>
The repeated burglaries were a cause for serious concern, with the
ruling African National Congress spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa saying that
it was "mind-boggling" Mbeki's home could be violated in the presence
of members of the SAPS VIP Protection Unit.
</P>
<P>
"It will not be preposterous to suggest collusion or involvement of
the SAPS VIP Protection Unit in the matter," said Mamoepa on Sunday in
a statement in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition National Party spokesman for safety and
security, Andre Fourie, said in response the police service should be
jacked up to protect the public.
</P>
<P>
Fourie was also critical of the highest attention being paid to
what he termed minor losses by cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
"How ridiculous that security for these minor losses by cabinet
ministers all of a sudden requires the highest attention. One can only
ask with tears in one's eyes: What about the man in the street?" he
added. enditem

