<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAUP Conference Held in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese universities and
colleges are trying to strengthen their relations and promote
cooperation with foreign universities.
</P>
<P>
"China wishes to know more about and be known more by the rest
of the world," said Wei Yu, vice-minister of the State Education
Commission (SEC), in her opening remarks at an international
conference held in Shanghai here today.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Conference of the International Association of
University Presidents (IAUP) opened today at Fudan University, one
of China's most prestigious universities based in Shanghai. This
is the first IAUP conference ever held in China. Over 150
university presidents from dozens of countries and regions,
including China, the United States, Australia, the Philippines,
attended the two-day conference.
</P>
<P>
"The ongoing conference reveals that Chinese educationists have
extended exchanges with their foreign colleagues," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
Attendants planned to discuss the development of higher
education and human resources in the Pacific region. Yang Fujia,
academician of the Chinese Academy of Science and president of
Fudan University, was elected the conference chairman. IAUP
president Donald Gerth was the foreign chairman of the conference.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jia'er, president of Beijing University, made a report on
China's higher education at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
IAUP, founded in 1964, is an international organization aiming
to promote cooperation and exchanges among universities in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over 5,000 foreign scholars have
participated in more than 140 international conferences held in
China. Colleges and universities affiliated to the SEC have sent
2,099 scholars abroad to attend 1,355 conferences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
