<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Confers with Western Samoan Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo
conferred with Western Samoan Deputy Prime Minister Tuilaepa
Sailele Malielegaoi here today.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that with joint efforts, Sino-Western Samoan friendly
and cooperative relations have achieved sustained sound, and
stable development since the two countries were linked
diplomatically more than 20 years ago, although the international
situation has changed greatly.
</P>
<P>
He added that leaders of the two countries have had a exchange
of visits over the past years, and that bilateral cooperation has
been expanded year after year in economy, trade, and culture, with
evident progress being made.
</P>
<P>
A trade agreement to be signed between the two sides will help
boost bilateral cooperation on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit, and will provide easy access for smoothly expanding
bilateral trade between the two countries, Wu noted.
</P>
<P>
Tuilaepa Sailele Malielegaoi said that Western Samoa places
importance on advancing its relations with China, and that
bilateral relations have been close since the two countries forged
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
The Western Samoan government adheres to its "one China"
policy, and will continue cooperating with China on issues of
common concern in the international forums, including the United
Nations, Malielegaoi said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that his government and people thanked the
Chinese government and people for their long-time charitable
assistance and support to Western Samoa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wu expressed his appreciations to the Western Samoan
government for adhering to its "one China" stance.
</P>
<P>
Wu also briefed Malielegaoi on China's domestic political and
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, both sides agreed that the two governments
should make joint efforts to push bilateral relations forward.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Wu and Malielegaoi attended a signing ceremony
for a trade agreement between the two governments and an exchange
of letters concerning China's construction of a primary school in
Western Samoa as a free assistance.  
</P>
