<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Adds Detail, Quotes US Vice-President Arrives in Beijing to Start China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- US Vice-President Al Gore arrived
in Beijing from Tokyo this evening on a five-day official visit to
China at the invitation of Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
This is Gore's first trip to China since he took office in
1992. The vice-president is the highest-ranking US official to
visit China since the beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement delivered upon his arrival, Gore said he
is pleased to visit China when the two countries mark the 25th
anniversary of the Shanghai Communique.
</P>
<P>
"I've traveled here to reaffirm the vital importance of
relations between our nations, and to continue building a lasting
peace between China and the United States," said the
vice-president.
</P>
<P>
He cited a poem entitled "On Stork Tower" by Chinese Tang
Dynasty Poet Wang Zhihuan -- "If you desire a grander sight, you
must scale a greater height."
</P>
<P>
To see the "currents of greater confluence" in US-China
relations, said Gore, "we must continue to climb the steps of
Stork Tower. That is why I'm here. And that is why our two
presidents will themselves ascend the tower in the coming months."
</P>
<P>
Gore said he looks forward to the discussions with President
Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng and other Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
The special plane carrying Gore, his wife, and a delegation
landed at 19:00 at Beijing's Capital Airport. The vice-president
was greeted by Chen Jinhua, chairman of the Chinese Government
Reception Committee and Minister in charge of the State Planning
Commission, Chinese Ambassador to the US Li Daoyu, and Chinese
vice-foreign minister Li Zhaoxing.
</P>
<P>
Among Gore's over-150-member delegation were Leon Fuerth,
assistant to the vice-president for national security affairs,
John Gibbons, science advisor to the president of the Science and
Technology Policy Office, Charles Curtis, deputy secretary of
energy, and other government officials.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-President is scheduled to hold talks with Premier Li
Peng on Tuesday following a welcome ceremony. He will also meet
with President Jiang Zemin, Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji,
Vice-President Rong Yiren, and Vice-Chairman of the Standing
committee of the National People's Congress Tian Jiyun during his
stay in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president's tight schedule covers participation in a
Sino-US seminar on environment and development, a speech on
Sino-US relations at Qinghua University, and a meeting with
Chinese scholars. He also will visit a high school and the Palace
Museum and go sightseeing at the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Beijing, Gore and his party will tour Xi'an, capital
city of northwest China's Shaanxi province, and China's biggest
metropolis of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Gore's visit comes as Sino-US relations are improving after
President Jiang Zemin and President Bill Clinton met in Manila
last November. The visit is also seen as paving the way for the
exchange of state visits between Jiang and Clinton later this year
and the next.
</P>
<P>
US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited Beijing a
month ago, exchanging views with the Chinese side on bilateral
relations and international issues. That visit was seen by both
sides as being "helpful to maintaining the favorable momentum" in
bilateral ties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
