<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Effort to Evoke Colonialism Bound to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A spectre of colonialism is
still hovering over Africa.
</P>
<P>
Certain people, reluctant to lose their past paradise, are
nostalgically dreaming of a comeback of old and neo-colonialism
swept out of the African continent 30 years ago by the
torrential, surging tide of national independence.
</P>
<P>
Since last autumn, this handful of people, making an uproar
from both sides of the Atlantic, are doing their utmost to call
back colonialism, long cast aside by mankind as filth and dirt,
and advocating that the only way out for Africa is "reversing the
whole process (of decolonisation)" and actually "recolonising the
region."
</P>
<P>
Trevor Royle, autor of the book "Winds of Change: the End of
Empire in Africa", can be regarded as one of the outstanding
advocates of the "reversal" theory. Basing himself on the Great
Lakes crisis in central Africa which he describes as "African
nightmare", he has asserted that the "Africans are incapable of
ruling themselves", that only the European whites can save them.
He even went so far as to say that to stabilise the situation,
"any means necessary" can be resorted to, even if that meant
"bringing back the old system", including "the white man", who
Royle claims "still has a role to play in many African
countries", and so on and so forth.
</P>
<P>
Royle does not come singly. John Keegan, a so-called British
historian, also jumps out to preach "recolonisation". He wrote in
the Daily Telegraph that "the only way to curtail the bloodshed
and carnage" in Africa "was to reverse the decolonisation
process" and revive "old imperial values". In Royle's words, it
is "restoring a British presence in the region". Here "presence"
means out and out colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
While preaching "recolonisation" in Africa, these guardians of
colonialism also vigorously propagate the theory of "doom" for
Africa. Political columnist Matthew Parris of the Times in London
is a typical representative of those denounced by Kenyan
newspapers as "pessimists". He used his poisonous pen to give a
big publicity to the various negative sides of Africa, taking
much delight in talking about civil wars, violence, crisis,
natural calamities, refugees and Aids, etc. as though Africa is a
hell of misery. He then lamented that "things seem to be falling
apart across the African continent" and that "there is no hope
for Africa, no hope at all". Taking this lamentation of Parris'
as a treasure, Royle further declared that "the process of
decolonisation has been a dreadful failure", and hence returned
to his starting point that the only way out for Africa is
"recolonisation".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Effort to Evoke Colonialism Bound to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Meanwhile, there is no lack of
such "heroes" like Royle on the other side of the Atlantic. These
"heroes" wantonly vilify one African country as having no
"democracy" and slander another one as depriving the people of
"human rights". They even insult African leaders by name. Their
representative is no other than Joshua Hammer, a former Nairobi
Bureau chief of the Newsweek magazine. After basking in the
sunshine and tasting the rich flavour of coffee in Kenya for
years, Hammer turned his face and said that he "is happy to be
out of Kenya" because Kenya would "collapse". He predicted that
Kenya will "disintegrate" when President Moi retires from
politics. Kenyan media naturally rejected this absurdity, saying
that contrary to Hammer's wishes, Kenya did not split in the
past, nor will it in the future. It is the "stability of Kenya"
that "has annoyed all those prophets of doom," a Kenyan newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Like Europe and America, Africa has its own problems. However,
all the scars and wounds in Africa can find their expressions on
the corpse of colonialism. Since Trevor Royle and Jushua Hammer
and their ilk can write books, they are certainly not ignorant of
the history of Africa.
</P>
<P>
History tells us that before the 15th century, Africa was
already renowned in the world for its Nile and Congo river
civilisations and not much backward compared with Europe except
that it was not so expansionist and predatory by nature as those
European pirates, while the U.S.A. was yet to be born. It was
after the intrusion of the first Portuguese merchandise ship into
Africa in the year 1415 that Europeans began thronging into this
continent and opened their history of invading Africa. They sold
black slaves, plundered resources, seized land, devided spheres
of influence among themselves, established colonial rule,
sabotaged and thwarted the economic and social development in
Africa and brought endless miseries to the African people.
</P>
<P>
The Second World War changed the face of the world and also
the fate of Africa. The post war 20-year history was just a
history of colonialism being buried in Africa. Beginning from
1950s, the surging tide of national liberation and independence
drove the colonialists out of the African continent. Trevor Royle
himself has admitted that even a few years ago no one dared to
say that "empire was better than independence".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Effort to Evoke Colonialism Bound to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- However, it is just those who
built the Union Jack empire on the skeletons of Africans, those
who stood under the Stars and Stripes with their hands stained
with the blood of African freedom fighters such as Patrice
Lumumba and those who stirred up disturbances with their
"multiparty democracy" in Africa that are now laughing in
arrogance at the backwardness and unrest in Africa. While
discrediting Africa, they try to stage a comeback and restore
colonialism. They criticize Africa as having no "democracy", no
"human rights". Yet when Africa needs the joint effort of
international community to solve Zaire conflict, to save the tens
of thousands of refugees suffering in the flames of war and
groaning in illness, they cast their "human rights" to the winds,
hold their tongues and keep silent. Why so? They have their own
purposes. A Western ally of the United States describes this as a
"conspiracy of silence".
</P>
<P>
It is thought-provoking that those people who prescribed
"multiparty democracy" for Africa a few years ago are now
prescribing "recolonisation" for Africa. They first want to
reform Africa on their Western model, and then come back to rule
Africa once again. In advocating the restoration of colonialism,
they are actually bent on restoring their lost paradise.
</P>
<P>
The days are gone forever when colonialists could order about
in Africa. The African people have stood up firmly on their feet.
They are politically mature and progressing socially and
economically. They are doing their best and making painstaking
effort to solve their own problems. The Nairobi Summit 1, Nairobi
Summit 2 and the forthcoming Nairobi Summit 3 soon to be held in
Lome, capital of Togo, are evidence that Africans are capable of
managing their own affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
