<HEADLINE> China To Continue Ventures With MD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to cooperate
with the McDonnell Douglas Corporation after the American aircraft
manufacturer merges with Boeing, Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua
told the company's Chairman John McDonnell here today.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting in Zhongnanhai, the headquarters of the
Chinese central government, Zou said that China and the US
corporation have established a sound cooperative relationship,
which has played an active role in developing China's civil
aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and the United States have the opportunities
to cooperate in many fields of the economy. China's economic
growth will boost the expansion of its civil aviation
industry. China wishes to continue the mutually beneficial
cooperation with McDonnell Douglas, regardless whether or not it
merges with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
McDonnell said that the company's cooperative relations with
China is definitely very important to the new company that will be
formed by the merger.
</P>
<P>
McDonnell Douglas can assure its customers that they will
receive quality and life-long service for the company's products
after its merger with Boeing, he said.
</P>
<P>
McDonnell and his entourage came to China to inspect the
progress of the MD-90 aircraft project, a joint venture between
McDonnell Douglas and China. They will visit Shenyang, Xian,
Chengdu and Shanghai cities where the 150-seat trunk-line
passenger aircraft is manufactured.  
</P>
</TEXT>
