<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Funds To Help South China City Build Expressway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- America's US-China Economic,
Technological, and Cultural Development Center will invest 180
million US dollars to build a 31.9 km long expressway in south
China's Guangdong province, according to a letter of intent
reached between the Center and the city government of Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
The expressway, which starts from Zhuhai, a booming coastal
city in Guangdong, will be part of the Zhuhai-Jiangmen expressway
that is a major project in the province during the Ninth Five-Year
Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The to-be-built expressway will be in accordance with the state
expressway standards in the slightly hilly areas, with the
expected driving speed of 120 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted by the American Retirement Foundation and the City
Bank, the US-China Economic, Technological, and Cultural
Development Center will pay the entire cost of this section of the
expressway, which is 180 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The US side will be repaid by installments according to a
certain fixed-assets invested return rate. When the agreement
expires in 19 and a half years, all assets will belong to the
Chinese side.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
