<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Requests Arafat's Personal Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy today called on Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, currently
abroad, to return home to intervene personally in the current
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that Arafat should return home from abroad
immediately to make efforts to defuse the rising tension between
the two sides, the state-run Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is currently in Pakistan attending the summit of
Islamic Conference in a new bid to muster Arab and international
support in the dispute over Israel's plan to build a new Jewish
neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the summit Sunday, Arafat appealed to the Muslim
world for help to save the holy city of Jerusalem from Israel's
policies.
</P>
<P>
Levy said the current crisis needed the highest level
intervention, so a summit meeting between Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu should be held to find a
solution.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said he thought the peace process must
continue despite the difficulties, while reiterating Israel's
demands on Arafat's fulfilment of his obligations to combat
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Levy issued the call following a Palestinian spokesman's
rejection of Israel's demands on the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) to take tougher measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
A statement released after the cabinet meeting Sunday night put
forward six points on demanding the PNA strengthen the fight
against terror and stop the anti-Israeli propaganda and violence.
</P>
<P>
The statement made it clear that no progress in the peace
process could be achieved before the PNA lived up to its
obligations of fighting against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeineh, Arafat's media adviser, denounced the
Israeli demands as violations of the Interim Agreement signed by
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Following the calls from Palestinian officials on his
mediation in the current crisis, Israeli President Ezer Weizman
held a meeting today with the United States' ambassador to Israel
Martin Indyk.
</P>
<P>
But it remained unclear whether the two had discussed
seeking ways to defuse the current Israeli-Palestinian tension
and revive the stalled peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
