<HEADLINE> MD Chairman Says Cooperation with China to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The long-term cooperation between
US aircraft giant McDonnell Douglas and China will be even
stronger after the company merges with Boeing, said John
F. McDonnell, chairman of the Board of Directors of MD Corp, today
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
After the merger, which creates the world's largest aircraft
and space corporation, is completed, no production line will be
arbitrarily closed, and the market will be identified according to
demand, Mr. McDonnell told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The merger, which was announced last December, is waiting for
approval from the US government and the shareholders of both
companies, but is expected to materialize this year.
</P>
<P>
Mr. McDonnell is here to review the progress of MD Corp.'s
co-production of MD-90 trunk aircraft with China and to
demonstrate the company's strong support to the program, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I will visit the four Chinese aircraft makers in Shenyang,
Xi'an, Chengdu and Shanghai, where the program is being
undertaken. I will also meet relevant Chinese officials of the
industry", he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. McDonnell, who will become a member of the board of the
merged company, said that the new company will continue to support
both the production and sales of the China-produced MD-90 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
After reviewing MDC's 22-years cooperation with China, the
chairman said that China has already become a key market for MDC.
</P>
<P>
"The pace of China's development is amazing. We expect to
expand our cooperation with China", he said.
</P>
<P>
While MDC now holds about 20 percent of China's commercial
aircraft market, Mr. McDonnell expects the new company will hold a
majority market share and will continue to be committed to provide
the highest quality aircraft along with superior customer and
product support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
