<HEADLINE> 3 Children Killed Monthly in Lusaka in Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- At least three children are killed
monthly in Lusaka in traffic accidents during their
water-fetching errands, a civic organization has claimed.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Independent Monitoring Team (ZIMT) President Alfred Zulu
said here on Sunday that his organization's recent survey shows that
apart from the traffic accident deaths, children and women are
under-going other inhuman ordeals like rape while they toil to fetch
water.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia today quoted him as saying that some other
children fall into wells or eaten by crocodiles while drawing water.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government and authorities concerned to invest
heavily in the water sector and make water easily and safely
available to all.
</P>
<P>
Zulu said Zambia has the highest water availability per capita in
the southern African region which can be tapped through a huge
injection of private and public investment and appropriate
technologies.
</P>
<P>
Zulu made the remarks after touring water projects and plants in
rural areas as part of the commemoration of the World Water Day.
