<HEADLINE> 3 Convicted Killers Hanged in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Three Muslim Extremists convicted
of assassinating a prominent Sunni Muslim cleric were hanged at
dawn today in Beirut's Central Prison.
</P>
<P>
Their deaths raised to 11 the overall number of executions
since the end of Lebanon's civil war in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Those hanged were two Lebanese, Khaled Hamed, 27, and Ahmed
Al-Kassem, 24, and a Palestinian, Munir Abboud. They confessed
to be members of a radical Sunni group calling itself Osbat
Al-Ansar, or Partisans League.
</P>
<P>
The three were found guilty of murdering Sheikh Nizar Habali
as he emerged from his Beirut apartment to climb into his car on
July 31, 1995.
</P>
<P>
They were arrested shortly after they raked Halabi's
limousine with sub-machinegun fire in Beirut's Tarik Al-Jedideh
residential neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Halabi headed the Islamic Welfare Projects Association, a
pro-Syrian Sunni group also known as Ahbash.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi signed the death sentence last
Friday despite pleas for mercy made by several radical Muslim
groups.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese army and police took tightened security measures
since Sunday in Beirut and other major cities to head off
possible protests against the executions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
