<HEADLINE> Fuel Scarcity Claims 5 in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Five people died and 20 others
were severly wounded in a petrol station fire in southwest
Nigeria on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported today that the tragedy occurred at around
10:am in the town of Sagamu, Ogun State, when the nozzel of a pumping
machine fell to the concrete ground as anxious drivers were fighting
for it.
</P>
<P>
It is belived that when the nozzel fell to the ground, it
caused a spark and led to the tragic fire and an explostion, which
also burnt down 10 vehicles and nine motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
With a daily production of two million barrels of crude oil,
Nigeria is one of the largest oil producing country in the world.
However, poor-run refineries have been continuously causing fuel
shortage in this oil-rich nation.
</P>
<P>
According to a report today, the country's largest oil refinery in
Port-Harcourt City is now suffering a damage to its control unit which
has reduced its production by half.
</P>
<P>
Another major refinery in Delta State also went out production
early last week for unknown reasons, the same report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
