<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Prawns Production Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's production of
prawns fell from 1,500 tonnes in 1978 to 500 tonnes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Director General of Tanzania Fishing Research Institute,
Professor Philip Bwathondi, made the disclosure in Rufiji, eastern
Tanzania on Sunday, when accpompanying Vice-President Omar Ali
Juma in a tour of the Rufiji delta.
</P>
<P>
Bwathondi said that the production decline in Mtwara and Tanga
regions was caused by overfishing using illegal trawlers.
</P>
<P>
He complained that in 1989 he advised the authority to cut
down the number of trawlers operating along the Indian Ocean
coast but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
The director general added that Tanzania has been catching prawns
at a higher rate than the corresponding prawns reproductive rate,
which if left unchecked, would lead to the depletion of the resources.
</P>
<P>
Quoting figures from the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO),
Bwathondi said Tanzania was endowed with better climatic conditions
than Madagascar and Mozambique but earned less money from the fish
catch than the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
