<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plastics Industry Needs Foreign Technology, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- China's plastics processing
industry is developing very rapidly, with foreign technology and
investment highly expected, a Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past few years, China invested millions of U.S.
dollars to import machinery and raw materials," Chen Zhongping,
president of the China Plastics Processing Industry Association
(CPPIA) told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The results are encouraging, with the total output of plastic
products amounting to 7.17 million tons in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has set the target for the emerging industry during the
Ninth Five-Year Plan. The output will be raised from 6 million
tons in 1995 to 8 million tons in 2000, with the average annual
growth rate being around 8 percent, to satisfy the ever growing
needs of agriculture, construction, packaging and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The CPPIA, together with another nationwide industrial
organization -- China Light Industry Machinery Association
(CLIMA), is here to promote the Asian-Pacific International
Plastics and Rubber Industry Expo to be held this November in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They expected a high attendance at the expo, the first of its
kind, from both domestic and overseas traders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Officially Writes Off Namibia's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Finance Minister
Nangolo Mbumba today spoke highly of the South African
government's decision to write off the 282 million U.S. Dollar
debt owed by Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the write-off, which was a major relief for Namibia,
it has left the Namibian government with only small loans it had
to repay, Mbumba said after signing an agreement to this effect
with his South African counterpart Trevor Manuel in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The debt had occupied the Namibian government since
independence in 1990 and by writing it off, the government would
able to start crucial development projects, said Mbumba.
</P>
<P>
The agreement signified the start of a new bilateral relation
between South Africa and Namibia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Manuel also agreed that the agreement enabled better
understanding between the governments of South Africa and Namibia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporean Charged with Drug Trafficking in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A Singaporean was charged
with drug trafficking in a magistrate's court in Petaling Jaya
adjacent to the capital city today.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old Lee Li Chiang, a laborer from Ang Mo Kio in
Singapore, was alleged to have committed the offense at the Kuala
Lumpur International Airport near here on March 10, the Malaysian
news agency Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who carried ecstasy pills with a gross total weight of
2,288.5 grams, was charged under Section 39B (1) of the Dangerous
Drugs Act 1952 which carries a mandatory death sentence upon
conviction.
</P>
<P>
Ecstasy pills, which are a hallucinatory drug, contain
methylenedioxy methamphetamine, a substance which is listed under
the act.  
</P>
</TEXT>
