<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. African Gas Project Runs into Hitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The West African Gas Pipeline
Project, designed to transport Nigeria's natural gas to Ghana,
Togo and Benin, has run into a hitch.
</P>
<P>
According to a local newspaper, the Business Concord, today,
necessary funds and infrastructure are not yet in place.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a developer has not been appointed for the
260-million-U.S.-Dollar project, which is also being frustrated
by bureaucratic bottlenecks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The four countries involved signed an agreement in September
1995 for the construction, maintenance and operation of the gas
pipeline, and a steering committee was later established
comprising ministers responsible for petroleum or their
representatives in the four countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee has failed in coordinating the requests
for funds from various international sources and appointing a
project developer, it said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will make use of the associated gas being
flared in oil fields in Nigeria, is expected to save up to 500
million U.S. Dollars in energy costs over a 10-year period for
Ghana, Togo and Benin.
</P>
<P>
With the delay in beginning the construction, it is doubtful
whether the 1998 target for completion of the pipeline and other
facilities will be met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fixed Assets Investment Increases Steadily in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's industrial and
financial center, will continue to strengthen city infrastructure
construction and the development and opening up of the Pudong New
Area, and to guide fixed assets investment toward the service
trade.
</P>
<P>
An official of the municipal Statistics Bureau said that
Shanghai has invested 9.885 billion yuan (about 1.18 billion US
dollars) in fixed assets during the first two months of 1997, an
increase of 44 percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The investment in real estate was three billion yuan (about 357
million US dollars), up 2.1 billion yuan (about 250 million US
dollars) from the corresponding 1996 period, accounting for 30
percent of the municipal total fixed assets investment.
</P>
<P>
Spending on city infrastructure facilities, housing and service
trade in the first two months in 1997 was higher than the same
period of 1996. The Pudong New Area is still the construction
magnet, and has attracted a total investment of 3.035 billion yuan
(361 million US dollars), representing a 94 percent increase over
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the investment, the portion of domestic loans and foreign
funds has increased by 4.3 percentage points and 1.1 percentage
points, respectively, since the beginning of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Misunderstandings Between Iran and Gulf Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani said here today that his talks with the Arab leaders at
the OIC special summit helped clear the misunderstandings between
Iran and its Gulf neighbors "to a certain extent."
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, who attended the OIC special summit held here
Sunday to celebrate Pakistan's golden jubilee, made the remarks
when answering a question at a news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
To another question, Rafsanjani said Iran had offered a gas
pipeline to India through Pakistan, However, Islamabad and New
Delhi could not strike an agreement and the proposed pipeline
would end in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said a "difficult and costly," project was under
consideration to provide gas to India through sea waters.
</P>
<P>
When asked about reports of a possible U.S. attack on Iran, he
said, "there are chances of any incident to take place at any
time."
</P>
<P>
However, he said Washington never benefited from harboring
animosity against Tehran.
</P>
<P>
On Afghanistan, the Iranian President said Iran did not provide
military assistance to any of the Afghan groups as "we are opposed
to war."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Tehran had been providing humanitarian
assistance to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran was not opposed to holding talks with the Afghan Taliban
militia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Teheran had invited the Taliban to attend the inter-Afghan
dialogue it hosted, but it did not turn up at the meeting, he
said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the establishment of a economic community
among the Muslim countries, Rafsanjani said that it could not be
achieved until the economies of these countries develop to similar
levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Effort to Evoke Colonialism Bound to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The following is a commentary
entitled "Effort to Evoke Colonialism Bound to Fail" by
correspondents Zhang Xijun and Chen Qimin:
</P>
<P>
A spectre of colonialism is still hovering over Africa.
</P>
<P>
Certain people, reluctant to lose their past paradise, are
nostalgically dreaming of a comeback of old and neo-colonialism
swept out of the African continent 30 years ago by the
torrential, surging tide of national independence.
</P>
<P>
Since last autumn, this handful of people, making an uproar
from both sides of the Atlantic, are doing their utmost to call
back colonialism, long cast aside by mankind as filth and dirt,
and advocating that the only way out for Africa is "reversing the
whole process (of decolonisation)" and actually "recolonising the
region."
</P>
<P>
Trevor Royle, autor of the book "Winds of Change: the End of
Empire in Africa", can be regarded as one of the outstanding
advocates of the "reversal" theory. Basing himself on the Great
Lakes crisis in central Africa which he describes as "African
nightmare", he has asserted that the "Africans are incapable of
ruling themselves", that only the European whites can save them.
He even went so far as to say that to stabilise the situation,
"any means necessary" can be resorted to, even if that meant
"bringing back the old system", including "the white man", who
Royle claims "still has a role to play in many African
countries", and so on and so forth.
</P>
<P>
Royle does not come singly. John Keegan, a so-called British
historian, also jumps out to preach "recolonisation". He wrote in
the Daily Telegraph that "the only way to curtail the bloodshed
and carnage" in Africa "was to reverse the decolonisation
process" and revive "old imperial values". In Royle's words, it
is "restoring a British presence in the region". Here "presence"
means out and out colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
While preaching "recolonisation" in Africa, these guardians of
colonialism also vigorously propagate the theory of "doom" for
Africa. Political columnist Matthew Parris of the Times in London
is a typical representative of those denounced by Kenyan
newspapers as "pessimists". He used his poisonous pen to give a
big publicity to the various negative sides of Africa, taking
much delight in talking about civil wars, violence, crisis,
natural calamities, refugees and Aids, etc. as though Africa is a
hell of misery. He then lamented that "things seem to be falling
apart across the African continent" and that "there is no hope
for Africa, no hope at all". Taking this lamentation of Parris'
as a treasure, Royle further declared that "the process of
decolonisation has been a dreadful failure", and hence returned
to his starting point that the only way out for Africa is
"recolonisation".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there is no lack of such "heroes" like Royle on the
other side of the Atlantic. These "heroes" wantonly vilify one
African country as having no "democracy" and slander another one
as depriving the people of "human rights". They even insult
African leaders by name. Their representative is no other than
Joshua Hammer, a former Nairobi Bureau chief of the Newsweek
magazine. After basking in the sunshine and tasting the rich
flavour of coffee in Kenya for years, Hammer turned his face and
said that he "is happy to be out of Kenya" because Kenya would
"collapse". He predicted that Kenya will "disintegrate" when
President Moi retires from politics. Kenyan media naturally
rejected this absurdity, saying that contrary to Hammer's wishes,
Kenya did not split in the past, nor will it in the future. It is
the "stability of Kenya" that "has annoyed all those prophets of
doom," a Kenyan newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Like Europe and America, Africa has its own problems. However,
all the scars and wounds in Africa can find their expressions on
the corpse of colonialism. Since Trevor Royle and Jushua Hammer
and their ilk can write books, they are certainly not ignorant of
the history of Africa.
</P>
<P>
History tells us that before the 15th century, Africa was
already renowned in the world for its Nile and Congo river
civilisations and not much backward compared with Europe except
that it was not so expansionist and predatory by nature as those
European pirates, while the U.S.A was yet to be born. It was
after the intrusion of the first Portuguese merchandise ship into
Africa in the year 1415 that Europeans began thronging into this
continent and opened their history of invading Africa. They sold
black slaves, plundered resources, seized land, devided spheres
of influence among themselves, established colonial rule,
sabotaged and thwarted the economic and social development in
Africa and brought endless miseries to the African people.
</P>
<P>
The Second World War changed the face of the world and also
the fate of Africa. The post war 20-year history was just a
history of colonialism being buried in Africa. Beginning from
1950s, the surging tide of national liberation and independence
drove the colonialists out of the African continent. Trevor Royle
himself has admitted that even a few years ago no one dared to
say that "empire was better than independence".
</P>
<P>
However, it is just those who built the Union Jack empire on
the skeletons of Africans, those who stood under the Stars and
Stripes with their hands stained with the blood of African
freedom fighters such as Patrice Lumumba and those who stirred up
disturbances with their "multiparty democracy" in Africa that are
now laughing in arrogance at the backwardness and unrest in
Africa. While discrediting Africa, they try to stage a comeback
and restore colonialism. They criticize Africa as having no
"democracy", no "human rights". Yet when Africa needs the joint
effort of international community to solve Zaire conflict, to
save the tens of thousands of refugees suffering in the flames of
war and groaning in illness, they cast their "human rights" to
the winds, hold their tongues and keep silent. Why so? They have
their own purposes. A Western ally of the United States describes
this as a "conspiracy of silence".
</P>
<P>
It is thought-provoking that those people who prescribed
"multiparty democracy" for Africa a few years ago are now
prescribing "recolonisation" for Africa. They first want to
reform Africa on their Western model, and then come back to rule
Africa once again. In advocating the restoration of colonialism,
they are actually bent on restoring their lost paradise.
</P>
<P>
The days are gone forever when colonialists could order about
in Africa. The African people have stood up firmly on their feet.
They are politically mature and progressing socially and
economically. They are doing their best and making painstaking
effort to solve their own problems. The Nairobi Summit 1, Nairobi
Summit 2 and the forthcoming Nairobi Summit 3 soon to be held in
Lome, capital of Togo, are evidence that Africans are capable of
managing their own affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Labor leader Tony Blair and the Shadow Chancellor Gordon
Brown Sunday stepped up Labor's efforts to woo business by
promising a seat for the Confederation of British Industry on a
high-level committee set up to prepare for Britain's presidency of
the European Union in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- France and Germany will Tuesday launch a fresh initiative
for closer co-operation on EU defence policy, in an effort to
reinvigorate the Maastricht treaty review conference.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- Firms would be forced by law to recognise and negotiate with
unions where they are supported by a majority of the workforce,
under far-reaching proposals revealed in a leaked copy of Labor's
business manifesto due to be launched after Easter.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Defence Sunday night described as +pure
speculation+ reports that senior Army officers are drawing up a
new code of moral conduct which would in effect end the ban on
homosexuality in the service.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite strenuous efforts by Britain's main parties to woo
the female voter, women still feel they are being ignored and that
their priorities differ strongly from the issues identified for
them by the politicians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
