<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: African Leaders Step Up Peace Efforts to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 24 (Xinhua) -- An extraordinary summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) will be held in Lome, capital
of Togo, on March 26 on the escalating Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
Just on the eve of the OAU mini-summit, a meeting called
Nairobi Summit III will also be convened here to seek a lasting
peaceful solution to the Zaire conflict.
</P>
<P>
It is apparent that African leaders are stepping up their
efforts to bring peace to the war-torn country, indicating
Africa's commitment to resolving its own problems.
</P>
<P>
Since taking up arms in eastern Zairea last October, the
Tutsi-led rebels have controlled one fifth of the Zairean
territory, the third largest country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
They are still advancing on several fronts, threatening to end
the 32-year-old rule of President Mobutu Sese Seko and topple his
government.
</P>
<P>
Asked about which side the OAU supports, OAU Secretary-General
Salim Ahmed Salim said that "we support the end of the conflict
and the work toward this goal", stressing that "we are totally
committed to the unity, stability, security and territorial
integrity of Zaire".
</P>
<P>
Considering that Africa's conflicts must be resolved by
itself, African leaders have been making diplomatic efforts to
end the Zaire conflict affecting the entire Great Lakes region
since its outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Kenya has hosted three regional summits initiated
by President Daniel arap Moi to discuss how to bring peace back
to Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders present at the Nairobi Summit I on
November 5 recommended that the United Nations deploy a neutral
security force in eastern Zaire to open up temporary sanctuaries
and safe corridors for displaced persons and returning refugees
to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
And the December 16 Nairobi Summit II mandated four heads of
state of Kenya, Zimbabwe, South Africa and Cameroun to work out a
formula for the restoration of peace in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Kenyan President Moi went to Zaire to meet
Zairean President Mobutu and discussed with him the worsening
situation in Zaire and the peace efforts of the regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
All these peace efforts by African leaders have contributed to
the adoption of a five-point peace plan on Zaire by the United
Nations Security Council on February 18.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan provides for an immediate ceasefire, the
withdrawal of all foreign forces from Zaire, negotiations and
elections and the protection of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Zairean government has accepted the peace plan while the
rebels still insist on negotiations before a ceasefire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: African Leaders Step Up Peace Efforts to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The conflicting parties were urged
to "unconditionally accept and implement" the peace plan by the
African leaders at the March 19 summit in Nairobi, capital of
Kenya, which called for a truce and talks.
</P>
<P>
They also underscored the importance of establishing a
mechanism for the implementation of the U.N. peace plan, to which
they said Africa should make "its own significant contributions".
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Zaire was represented by Prime Minister Kengo
wa Dondo and it is the first time that Zaire has attended such a
meeting. "With Zaire's participation" in the one-day summit, "the
search for peace will indeed gain considerable momentum", said
President Moi.
</P>
<P>
Zaire did not turn up in the last two Nairobi summits for the
attendance of Uganda and Rwanda, which are accused by Zaire of
sending troops to fight in eastern Zaire along with the rebels.
Both deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
Late February, South African President Nelson Mandela met a
special envoy of President Mobutu and rebel leader Laurent Kabila
separatedly to explore possibilities of direct negotiations
between the two warring sides.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's bid for peace in Zaire could be the start of a
genuine African effort to seize the initiative in resolving
Africa's conflicts, analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
One of his advisers said President Mandela is anxious to bring
the initiative for conflict resolution and control of the process
back to the African continent, because he sometimes feels that
western countries do not always act in the best interests of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of France which has been calling for
international intervention, western powers like the United States
are reluctant to send troops for peacekeeping in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said as Zaire has lost its strategic importance,
western powers turn cold shoulders to the Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, in his talks with Mandela on March 20, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged African countries including
South Africa to play a larger role in peace-keeping operations in
their own continent.
</P>
<P>
Both Annan and Mandela said they are optimistic about a
peaceful solution to the Zairean conflict.
</P>
<P>
This special OAU summit is expected to focus, among other
things, on how to persuade the two warring sides to pursue an
immediate ceasefire and direct negotiations which would create
the necessary environment to facilitate a peaceful settlement to
the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
