<HEADLINE> Forged Zambian Currency Notes in Circulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Zambia has warned the
public that forged local currency notes with the highest
denomination of 10 thousand Kwacha (about 7.7 U.S. Dollars) are in
circulation in the country, according to a public notice from the
bank available here today.
</P>
<P>
After giving some details of the features of the forged notes,
the bank urged the public to be "extra careful when transacting
with Kwacha notes, especially those of higher denomination."
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who comes across a suspected forged notes should
report to the nearest police station," the bank's notice said.
</P>
<P>
The 10-thousand-Kwacha notes, together with notes bearing the
denomination of five thousand Kwacha and one thousand Kwacha,
were put into circulation at the end of the year 1996. Earlier,
the highest denomination was five hundred Kwacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
