<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Discuss Common Regional Currency, Zero </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Government leaders of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) are expected to
discuss the introduction of a U.S. Dollar-pegged currency for the
region and the establishment of zero tariffs among member states.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here on Sunday by COMESA Acting General
Secretary Joel Mwenche who said a COMESA summit meeting will be
convened in Lusaka early next month.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new regional currency is to replace the recently
abolished Uapta currency that was used in the organization in the
past. Mwenche said: "The issue has been approved by COMESA
central bank governors."
</P>
<P>
Apart from approving the new currency, the heads of states
will also seriously consider the movement of COMESA member states
towards the establishment of zero tariffs among them, which should
be in place by the year 2000, according to Mwenche.
</P>
<P>
COMESA was formed by 20 countries in eastern and southern
Africa in 1994 to replace the old organization of Preferential
Trade Area (PTA) of Eastern and Southern Africa for further
economic integration in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
