<HEADLINE> Rebels Penetrate Southwestern Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) have penetrated into southwestern Uganda
since they had sustained heavy loss in the west, "the New Vision"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"While the number of ADF rebels in Rwenzori mountain ranges in
Kasese is steadly decreasing, there are reports about increased
rebel movements in forests of Bushenyi, Rukungiri and Kisoro
districts," a security official in Kasese district told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The security official asking to be remained anonymous said
there has been a bitter clash between the government troops and
ADF rebels in Bushenyi district on Wednesday. An unspecified
number of rebels were killed in the battle, and some government
soldiers had also been wounded.
</P>
<P>
ADF initially intended to establish their bases in the
Rwenzori Mountain areas in Kasese District in the west since they
invaded Uganda last November. Two months later, the Ugandan
authority announced they have uprooted the hideouts of ADF rebels in
the mountain, but there were still some remnants in the district.
Later reports said some ADF rebels surviving the mopping-up
operations of the government troops infiltrated into Kabarole
district east of Kasese, and Bushenyi district south of Kasese
district. Rugungiri and Kisoro are still south of Bushenyi and
are bordering Zaire.
</P>
<P>
ADF had some 1,000 soldiers in its ranks last November but now
has some small scattered groups. But an earlier report said ADF
rebels abducted some 800 civilians and are trying to
train them.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 local people have been displaced since
February in Kasese District due to the persistent harassment of
ADF, a local official told the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK Association of Banks Chairman Confident in HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Chris Langley, chairman of the
Hong Kong Association of Banks, has voiced full confidence in the
future of Hong Kong as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
"To me, there is no question Hong Kong is already a preeminent
international financial center," Langley said in a recent
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"And what is going to ensure the continuing preeminence of Hong
Kong is its increasingly close linkage with the economy of the
Chinese mainland as that economy continues to grow and prosper,"
the banker noted.
</P>
<P>
Langley is also general manager Hong Kong and China of the
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation (HongkongBank), the
largest bank in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I'm naturally very pleased to have the opportunity to be the
chairman (of the association) in the very special year," he said.
</P>
<P>
The association is a representative body of all licensed banks
in Hong Kong and its chairmanship rotates among the three
note-issuing banks -- Bank of China, HongkongBank and Standard
Chartered Bank.
</P>
<P>
Langley pointed out that Hong Kong is "the only international
financial center which can represent itself as a gateway to and a
services center for China."
</P>
<P>
The very favorable location will "become more and more
favorable" as the economy of the Chinese mainland develops, he
said.
</P>
<P>
And in terms of corporate regional headquarters, Hong Kong
outnumbered every other country and region in Southeast Asia put
together, he said.
</P>
<P>
That's very important statistics as a certain number of centers
like to "talk quite loudly" about their success in attracting
regional headquarters, he added.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure they are successful, but they are not in the same
league as Hong Kong is, because no other centers can replicate the
basic advantages of location, scales and the success record that
Hong Kong has."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is well-known as a place where "the entire range of
financial services, from insurance to most sophisticated financial
 derivatives, are all available," Langley stressed, adding that
over 85 of the world's top 100 banks operate in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
And after the handover, the financial system of Hong Kong will
remain unchanged as guaranteed by the Basic Law and the principle
of "one country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
So briefly, "I'm very confident indeed of the future of Hong
Kong as an international financial center," Langley said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the morale of local financial sector in the final
lap of the transition period, the chairman claimed: "The
confidence level of the industry remains very high."
</P>
<P>
"Our bank has always taken a view that on July 1 and
thereafter, it's going to be business as usual," he added.
</P>
<P>
"And business as usual, as far as we can tell, from projections
we have and projections government has, means good business," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Based on last year's 4.6 percent rise in the gross domestic
product, a higher rate -- 5.5 percent -- was predicted for this
year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stepped into the year 1997 with very buoyant stock
and property markets, with consumer spending being maintained at
high levels.
</P>
<P>
Besides, good tourist figures are foreseeable as there will be
a lot of interest in Hong Kong during the historic year, while
trade volumes are expected to rise as well.
</P>
<P>
"So confidence is there and people are looking forward to a
better year in 1997 than in 1996," Langley reassured.
</P>
<P>
The whole spectrum of the banking sector performed very well in
1996, with an average of 21 percent profit growth recorded,
according to figures released here last week by a global
investment bank, Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old banker has served the HSBC Group, of which
HongkongBank is a founding member, for more than 30
years. Responsible for HongkongBank's operations in both Hong Kong
and the Chinese mainland, Langley called himself "a regular
visitor" to Beijing, Shanghai and other major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
"I was always most impressed by the progress I see," he said.
</P>
<P>
HongkongBank has six branches and four representative offices
in the mainland and is still expanding its business involvement
there.
</P>
<P>
"We are very interested in increasing our presence. We regard
China as a very major opportunity for our bank," the banker said.
</P>
<P>
He expected much more "cross-flow business opportunities" for
Hong Kong and the mainland after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Although there is already a huge amount of business done
between Hong Kong and the interior areas, it is just the
beginning, he said. "We are on the first step of a very, very
exciting power."  
</P>
</TEXT>
