<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Fund to Cooperate With S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Africa
Investment Fund (COMAFIN), an initiative setup to assist the
development of Commonwealth states, would join forces with South
African companies interested in investing in neighboring and
regional countries.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Companies and Markets today quoted COMAFIN
Chairman Joseph Pillay as saying that the organization would be
holding discussions with interested businessmen and he hoped the
discussions would lead to joint venture partnerships in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
The organization was launched by South African President
Nelson Mandela in London last July in a bid to link Commonwealth
states in Africa with their counterparts across the world through
cross-border investments and project initiatives, Pillay said.
</P>
<P>
Investors in the fund included the Commonwealth Development
Corporation, the Development Bank of South Africa, and the
governments or investment agencies of Botswana, Brunei, Malaysia,
Singapore and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
COMAFIN had already committed about 63.5 million U.S. dollars
for projects in Commonwealth Africa.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 7.3 million U.S. dollars has been invested in
four projects in Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
These projects covered the areas of intensive agriculture,
tourism commercial property, manufacturing, mining and
infrastructure, power, transport and telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
