<HEADLINE> Geographic Information System Makes Social Research Easy: Workshop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Researchers attending a
workshop here today explored the advances in using a geographic
information system (GIS) in population analysis and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The GIS is a computerized system for collecting geographic data
 and information from various sources such as satellite or aerial
pictures. These data can be used to study landscape, to analyze
population changes, to develop social and economic policies and
even to work out marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
A workshop, organized by the Chinese University of Hong Kong,
was opened here today to provide chances for researchers to
exchange their views on how to apply the system worldwide. The
participants came from Hong Kong, Taiwan, the Chinese mainland,
the United States and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Professor Lin Hui of the Chinese University of Hong Kong, also
chairman of the two-day workshop, said that the GIS is of great
help to those who have to handle a great deal of data carefully
and precisely when they devise development strategies or tap
geographical issues such as migration, urbanization and
environmental changes.
</P>
<P>
Relying the GIS, Prof. Lin would speak at the workshop about
the economic implications of the Beijing-Kowloon railway in
China. Other topics include the role of the GIS in handling
population problems in China, Europe and the United States, and
many other social and economic issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
