<HEADLINE> Eye Care Program for Chinese Mainland Launched in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Polytechnic
University and CIBA Vision signed an agreement on launching a
five-year project to promote education and public awareness
towards eye care in the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
The program is funded by 5 million HK dollars jointly provided
by CIBA Vision and the Novartis Foundation for Cooperation and
Sustainable Development.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Glen Bradley, chief executive officer of CIBA Vision, said
that about one out of every two Chinese require vision correction
for myopia and the program is to increase vision care options for
those individual sufferers in the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
George Woo, professor and chair of Optometry and dean of Health
and Social studies of the university, said that in support of this
initiative, his university will help different medical and
technological institutions in the Chinese mainland to establish
their own undergraduate programs in optometry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the first program will start in Sun-Yat Sen
University of Medical Sciences in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
In time, he said, the program will create an expanded pool of
competent practitioners with enhanced clinical and professional
skills.
</P>
<P>
"Our teaching staff will also give lectures at various medical
and technological universities and hospitals in the Chinese
mainland, with a view to fostering collaborative research programs
with them in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Launched in 1996, CIBA Vision's China Ophthalmic Education
Program has enabled medical and optometric educators,
optometrists, ophthalmologists and opticians to enhance their
clinical expertise through education and intensive training.
</P>
<P>
Last year, nearly 100 qualified physicians and educators in
China completed an intensive training program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
