<HEADLINE> IMAX Film on African Elephant being Shot in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- An IMAX film on the African
elephant is being shot by an Australian crew in the Amboseli
National Park of Kenya, the East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The film is expected to be completed in July this year and to
be seen by more than 100 million people the world over in 1998,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Michael Laulfield, Producer/Director of the film
"the African Elephant", the decision on Kenya as a location was
made after rejecting other sites in Africa, including South
Africa, Tanzania, Zimbabwe and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
There has been a lot of research on the elephant in the park
for the last 23 years, resulting in extensive data about African
elephants.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, Laulfield noted, the scientific consultant of
the film was very favorable of Amboseli as the location.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the 40 minutes large-than-life IMAX screen
feature will not be shown in Kenya as there are only 200 IMAX
screens in the world and only one in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The film producer noted that his crew is taking pictures in
the open jungle using a platform, adding that in the Amboseli,
one can get closer to the elephant than anywhere else in the
world.
</P>
<P>
"The elephants come right up to the platform and some even use
their trunks to nudge our feet, which is impossible elsewhere,"
he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Laulfield paid tribute to Kenyans on what they are doing in
the conservation of wildlife, but said that the conflict between
the people and the elephant should be discussed fully.
</P>
<P>
The film director described the wildlife as an enormous
economic asset and an "important African resource", adding that
the lifting of the ban on ivory trade would be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
The film's scientific consultant, Ian Douglas Humilton, who
has been working with the African elephant for the last 30 years,
believed that the lifting of the ban on ivory trade would wipe
out the elephant population in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Hamilton, who has written two books on the African elephant
including "Battle for the Elephant in 1992", noted that since the
implementation of the ban, the number of the African elephant had
stabilized, if not increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
