<HEADLINE> Latvian PM: Bring Baltic States "In From Cold" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Latvian Prime Minister
Andris Skele said today that it was dangerous to keep the Baltic
states out of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
In a speech to German bankers in Frankfurt, Skele warned that
it could create a breeding ground for conflict between the East
and the West if Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia were excluded from
the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
"We think it is impermissible to leave any grey zone where
conflict between the East and the West could germinate anew,"
Skele was quoted by the Deutsche Presse-Agentur as saying.
</P>
<P>
The NATO and EU memberships would contribute to the security of
the Baltic states as well as the rest of Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his country needed to further integrate its
economy into Western Europe. 
</P>
