<HEADLINE> A New Face for Old Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city Tianjin
has injected 1.6 billion yuan in total investment to rebuild eight
tattered streets and derelict houses with a total coverage of 2.6
million square metres within its old urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Construction of these projects started early this month, and
will be finished by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The eight streets to be rebuilt include "Fu'an Street" and
"Rongye Street", which are about a century old. After being
rebuilt, these streets will be widened to 30 to 40 meters, putting
on a new face.
</P>
<P>
Modern buildings will be built along both sides of the eight
streets for residents to live in, who have moved out from those
shattered houses.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that local residents have been so pleased with the
government's move that they call it a "Benefit People" project.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has paid great attention to construction of roads over
the past few years, having built three ring roads around the city
and 14 roads radiating to connect the city's center with its outer
areas.
</P>
<P>
But traffic jams still took place in the crowded old urban
areas frequently, and the houses there were ruined.
</P>
<P>
So the Tianjin municipal government raised 1.6 billion yuan
this year to fund reconstruction of the old urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Local observers say that this is a stepping-stone for Tianjin
to build itself into an international metropolis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
