<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Power Industry To Offer More Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The power industry in Asia is
predicted to offer more investment opportunities than any other
sectors in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Chesser, head of regional power research of BZW Asia
Limited, said that the power industry has become a favorite with
institutional investors because of its stability in profit
earning, transparency in operation and predictability in future
performance.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that independent power producers (IPPs) will
account for 30 to 40 percent of all new generating assets over the
next few years thanks to the liberation of power markets in many
Asian countries. The IPPs are set to play a more important role in
boosting the regional electricity output.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the total market capitalization of Asian power
stocks has reached 69 billion US dollars, of which only 35 percent
are free float shares, according to BZW Asia. Moreover, about
half of the free float stocks are dominated by Hong Kong power
generators, showing that the power sectors in most part of Asia
are still undergoing a process of liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Chesser forecast that the free float shares will double in
two or three years to make Asian power stocks a lucrative
investment. BZW Asia estimated that initial public offerings by
Asian power companies will amount to 15 to 20 billion US dollars
in the next two years, and China, pushed by huge demand, will take
the lion's share of the increased generating power.
</P>
<P>
BZW, a division of Barclays Bank PLC, is responsible for
wholesale banking, securities dealing and investment banking
services within the Barclays Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
