<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World TB Day Held in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Opened its World TB
Day in Time Square this morning to call for concerted effort to
combat tuberculosis in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the "World TB Day" held here this
morning, Katherine Fok, secretary for Health and Welfare, said
that despite all the breakthroughs in the prevention and treatment
of the disease, tuberculosis remains a threat to the world.
</P>
<P>
She said that tuberculosis can become a main cause of death in
Hong Kong if people are not on the vigilance in combating the
disease.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, there are about 6,000 new TB cases each year and
the situation should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
She said that appropriate treatment and strengthening of public
education remain the most effective ways to prevent and combat
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about one third of the world's population
are infected with the disease which claims some 3 million lives a
year.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the World Health Organization had called for the
adoption of the DOTS (Directly Observed Treatment Short-course)
treatment which Hong Kong had already adopted in the 1970s and
should be considered very advance on this aspect.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are 17 TB and Chests Clinics under the
Department of Health which provide free services to TB patients
throughout the territory.
</P>
<P>
On public education, she said she hoped that the community
could render their support to activities that promote
understanding of tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
The World TB Day exhibition held in Times Square today was
organized by the Department of Health, Hospital Authority and the
Hong Kong Tuberculosis, Chest and Heart Disease Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
