<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europeans Push for Greater ATP Voice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- European ATP Tour players have
formed an association aimed at increasing European representation
on the circuit's board of directors and making their voice heard
in tour matters.
</P>
<P>
The group was founded last week with world number-two Thomas
Muster of Austria tipped to represent top ten players.
</P>
<P>
There are 64 Europeans among the ATP's top 100 players, and
more than 35 ATP players live in Monte Carlo. They were reportedly
unhappy to see the circuit's European office moved from Monaco to
London.
</P>
<P>
ATP chief executive officer Mark Miles said greater political
involvement by European players was welcome and that their voting
power, if organized, could ensure a European member on the board
of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
