<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Rejects Israel's New Demands on Advancing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) today rejected Israel's demands that conditioned
progress in the peace process on its hardening fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeineh, media adviser to PNA President Yasser
Arafat, told the Israel Radio that he was "shocked" at the new
conditions set by the Israeli government on advancing the peace
process which is facing a deepening crisis following the recent
wave of violence.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released after the inner cabinet meeting
Sunday night, the Israeli government requested the PNA to
strengthen security cooperation with Israel in fighting against
"terrorism" and to stop incitement and hostile propaganda against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the PNA to launch an effective and
systematic crackdown on "terrorist" organizations, to punish and
transfer "terrorists" to Israel for trials and to collect illegal
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Rudeineh said the PNA would not accept these demands, which he
described as violating the interim agreement signed by the two
sides, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Palestinian officials were reportedly
asking Israeli President Ezer Weizman to mediate the current
crisis in order to resume the stalled peace talks, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, the ceremonial head of state in Israel, has long
played a mediating role between the two sides during times of
difficulties in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
PNA Minister of Culture and Information Yasser Abed Rabbo was
said to be ready to talk with Weizman on finding ways to break
the current deadlock that fueled the tense situation. But so far
it remained unclear if Weizman had agreed to accept the
Palestinian request, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel continued tightening screw on the PNA for
strengthening its fight against "terrorism" following last
Friday's suicide bombing in central Tel Aviv that killed three
Israelis and the bomber and injured more than 40 others.
</P>
<P>
The bombing was carried out by the Islamic militant group
Hamas which has been engaging in attacks against Israel. But the
Israeli government held the PNA directly responsible for the
attack.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Sunday night, Israeli army intelligence
chief Moshe Yaalon and Chief of Staff Amonon Lipkin Shahak clearly
blamed Arafat for giving the green light to Hamas and other
radical groups to launch attacks in protests over Israel's recent
moves to begin building a Jewish neighborhood in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Yaalon said that, while it was difficult to prove that Arafat
had specifically told the radical groups to carry out the
attacks, Arafat obviously sent out a message of approval during
a meeting with leaders of these organizations upon his return
from the United States two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Arafat had changed tactics to violent
confrontation because he felt threatened in his plans to set up
a Palestinian state with East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Shahak warned that the current situation could still
deteriorate because the radical groups had a tacit agreement
with the PNA allowing them to carry out more attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces are keeping high alert throughout the
country as security has been beefed up in public places in all
major cities. The total closure on the Palestinian territories
imposed following the Tel Aviv bombing remains in force to
prevent possible infiltration of extremists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Export Earning Declines by 9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has announced that its
export earning declined by nine percent while its balance-of-payment
deficit rose to 3.8 billion Birr (about 590 million dollars) in
the 1995/96 budget year.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Ministry of Trade and Industry said the
country in 1995-96 got 2.8 billion Birr (about 430 million
dollars) from foreign trade, accounting for 74 percent of the
targeted 3.8 billion Birr (about 590 million dollars) export
earnings.
</P>
<P>
The ministry primarily attributed the dramatic fall in the
export earning to the drop in the price of coffee on the world
market, and significant shortfalls in the hard currency earnings
of livestock, leather products and vegetables and fruit exports.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia exported 101,823 tons of coffee, which generated 64
percent or 1.8 billion Birr (about 280 million dollars) of the
total trade revenue.
</P>
<P>
The ministry pointed out that despite a 30 percent increase in
the volume of coffee export, earnings from the commodity declined
by 6 percent in 1995/96 compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the ministry, Ethiopia's import
expenditure dramatically rose to 6.6 billion birr (over one
billion dollars) in 1995/96, creating a 3.8 billion birr (about
590 million dollars) trade deficit. In the 1994/95
budget year, the import expenditure was 4.2 billion birr (about
660 million dollars) and the deficit was only 1.2 billion birr
(about 190 million dollars). enditem

=03240729

=03240736
NNNN
15:34 15:34 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
