<HEADLINE> Chinese Warships' U.S. Visit Described as New Chapter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN DIEGO, March 23 (Xinhua) - A Chinese vice admiral said here
today that the first visit to the continental United States by
three Chinese Warships has opened a new chapter in the annuals of
relations between the two navies.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yongguo, commander of the Chinese navy South China Sea
Fleet, said that the visit has deepened mutual understanding and
enhanced bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Two Chinese destroyers and an oiler are currently visiting the
U.S. naval base in San Diego, a port city in southern California.
They had spent four days in Pearl Harbor before their arrival here
on March 21.
</P>
<P>
The visit is of great historic significance and indicates a new
stage in the exchange of the two navies, said the vice admiral in
an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In San Diego the flotilla's visit has made a stir and naval
base officers said never before had so many people come to visit
foreign vessels. On the first day when the ships were open to the
public, 13,000 visitors were registered.
</P>
<P>
The flotilla will wind up its visit to the United States on
March 25 and proceeds to Mexico, Peru and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
