<HEADLINE> Malaysian King Calls for High Values to Overcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 Social Ills
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian King Tuanku
Ja'afar today stressed the need for high values and social ethics
to overcome the social problems facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The King described drug abuse and the influx of illegal
immigrants as the two major problems the country is now facing.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the Islamic Development Department will
be able to help the government tackle moral decline among the
youth and other social ills like drug abuse and AIDS," he said
when opening the first meeting of the third term of the ninth
Parliament here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the influx of illegal immigrants had caused various
problems like illegal settlements, forged travel documents,
doubtful marriages with locals and a rise in health care and
education costs.
</P>
<P>
"The government takes a serious view of these problems because
they pose a threat to national security, peace and harmony," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in view of the social problems facing the
society, the task of molding the young generation required
cautious handling and an integrated approach by everyone.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts will be stepped up to strengthen the family
institution because the government believes that a healthy, stable
and resilient family will produce citizens of caliber with
self-respect, he said.
</P>
<P>
Towards this end, the King said, religious teachings and faith
must be inculcated through various educational programs,
especially among the young generation, "to create high values and
social ethics like self-discipline, tolerance, love and respect
for each other". 
</P>
</TEXT>
