<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unabated Growth of Slums Reported in India's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The increasing number of slums
and large-scale encroachments on public land have made New Delhi,
capital of India, one of the largest slum-infested cities in the
country, according to a committee for urban affairs.
</P>
<P>
In its latest report tabled in the Lower House of Parliament
recently, the committee said "Spate of illegal and unauthorized
colonies have hampered the systematic and planned growth of
Delhi."
</P>
<P>
While the urban population of the country has been increasing
at the rate of about three percent a year, that of the urban slums
increasing at a rate of nine percent per year, said K.K.
Bhatnagar, chairman of the Housing and Urban Development
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented growth of urban slum population was due to
the lack of development of basic infrastructure facilities and the
inadequate availability of serviced land within affordable reach
of economically weaker sections of society, he said.
</P>
<P>
In its report, the committee has expressed its unhappiness with
the slow pace of construction of houses and flats for allotment to
wait-list registrants.
</P>
<P>
All-out efforts should have been made to construct and allot
the houses by this time, it said.
</P>
<P>
Necessary corrective measures should be taken immediately to
prevent the unabated growth of slums, encroachment of public land
and other unauthorized activities, the committee suggested.
</P>
