<HEADLINE> 38 Indian Teenagers Sent Back by Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A total of 38 Indian teenagers
came back to Mumbai (Bombay) Sunday night from Pakistan's port
city Karachi, local press said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a goodwill gesture, Pakistan sent back 38 Indian boys
allegedly straying into that country's territorial waters. The
boys had worked as crew on board fishing vessels sailing out of
Gujarat state in southern India.
</P>
<P>
They spent three years in Pakistan and most of them were taken
out of jail and rehabilitated by a local social worker Abudul
Sattar Edhi in children's homes in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"This gesture will help the relations between the two
countries," said Devjibhai Tandel, former member of Parliament
from Gujarat who arrived at the airport to receive the boys.
</P>
<P>
With the resumption of talks between foreign secretaries of
India and Pakistan from March 28 to 31, Indian External Affairs
Minister I.K. Gujral announced a number of steps to improve
people-to-people contacts with Pakistan in the Lower House on
March 20.
</P>
<P>
The steps included exemption to young and elderly Pakistan
visitors from reporting to the police, waiving visa fees for
senior citizens from across the border, increasing the number of
religious shrines in India open to Pakistan pilgrims and allowing
import of Pakistan books and periodicals.
</P>
<P>
These measures were designed to add to the goodwill between the
peoples of the two countries, Gujral said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
