<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Observes World TB Day with Emphasis on New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepal today observed the World
Tuberculosis (TB) Day by organizing various programs with an
emphasis on a newly introduced treatment, which doctors believe
would effectively cure the disease.
</P>
<P>
TB control officials here said that the Directly Observed
Treatment Short Course (DOTS) method, introduced in the country
last year, has been found effective in curbing the TB disease as
patients are given drugs under the strict supervision of doctors
or health workers.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's National Tuberculosis Center (NTC) last year launched a
program to implement the DOTS method, recommended by the World
Health Organization (WHO), in four of the country's 75 districts
on the trial basis.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary reports show, they said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 16,000 people die of tuberculosis
every year in Nepal and some 50,000 new cases are recorded in the
meantime.
</P>
<P>
Doctors working in the field said that the patients' failure to
complete their full course of drugs and TB's close linkage with
AIDS have made the disease more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
There is an urgent need to strengthen supervision on local
levels to ensure an expansion of the implementation of the DOTS
program, they said.
</P>
<P>
Nepali King Birendra in a message issued today on the occasion
of the World TB Day wished all concerned success in promoting
public awareness about the diagnosis, prevention and treatment of
the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
