<HEADLINE> HK Newspapers Call on People to Unite for Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- With Hong Kong's transition
entering the final 99-day period, Hong Kong newspapers today
carried commentaries to urge the people to unite and to contribute
wisdom to ensure Hong Kong's smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Commercial Daily said that Hong Kong's return to her
motherland is a major event for the Chinese nation. Toward this
end, the whole Hong Kong people should be united to promote Hong
Kong's handover.
</P>
<P>
It is a great creation that the Chinese government settles the
Hong Kong issue by peaceful means and implementation of the
principles of "One Country, Two Systems", "Hong Kong People
Governing Hong Kong" and high degree of autonomy, it said.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that unity is the impetus for the progress as well
as serves as a cornerstone for stability, adding that only the
unity of various sectors can guarantee Hong Kong's smooth
transition.
</P>
<P>
Sing Dao Daily said that facts have proved that some people's
worry about an instable situation in the territory around 1997 is
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
It said that the continued economic reforms and opening up and
sustained economic growth in the Chinese mainland will ensure the
implementation of the principle of "One Country, Two Systems" and
"Hong Kong People Governing Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
It said that at such a critical moment when Hong Kong will
return to China in less than 100 days, various sectors in the
territory should seek common ground while reserve differences so
as to preserve Hong Kong's prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao said since it is less than 100 days from Hong
Kong's return to her motherland, the Provisional Legislative
Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) is
facing heavy task.
</P>
<P>
It said that there are sufficient legal basis for the PLC to
legislate before June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
It called on the PLC members to take the overall interests of
the all the Hong Kong people into account to accelerate its work.
 
</P>
