<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Opposition Protests Arrest of Party Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) will hold a public meeting here today to
protest the attack and arrest of party workers and leaders
occurred on Sunday's nationwide strike.
</P>
<P>
The eight-hour strike enforced by the BNP was marked by
sporadic violence that left more than 200 injured including former
Home Minister Matin Chowdhury. At least 150 persons were arrested
in Dhaka on charge of damaging vehicles and disrupting normal
life.
</P>
<P>
BNP Secretary General Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan told a press
conference Sunday night that his party had no plan now to call a
fresh strike. The next course of action will depend on the
government's performance, he added.
</P>
<P>
The BNP called Sunday's strike to protest what it called the
government's giving transit facility to India and planned import
of power from that country, move to form a sub-regional grouping
and the crisis of power across Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
It was the first strike during the nine-month-old government of
Sheikh Hasina, who defeated BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia on last
June election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some business leaders expressed concern over the
renewed incidence of strikes and urged the BNP to avoid political
agitation taking into consideration its adverse impacts on the
growth of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Vice President of the Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and
Industry Laila Kabir said the renewed political agitation would
jeopardize the prospects for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"We want development and foreign investment. Any threat to
political stability would diminish our chances of doing well," she
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
