<HEADLINE> Well-off Farmers Help Poor Peers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Better-off farmers in Qidong
County of central China's Hunan Province have taken out five
million yuan from their pockets to sponsor local social welfare
projects, as a way to help their peers still locked in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Some 170 households of farmers have bid farewell to their
shabby houses, thanks to programs sponsored by farmers who became
rich with the progress of reform and opening.
</P>
<P>
Also, some 100 kilometers of roads and more than 100 bridges
have been built in the villages across the county in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
The better-off farmers also took out money to help the aged
people living alone and students who had economic difficulties
finishing schooling.
</P>
<P>
For example, the brothers of Fu Dingguo and Fu Dingzhong, in
Lingguan Township of the county, sank three wells and built a
three-km-long road in their village. In the past decade, the two
brothers have spent a total 100,000 yuan in different social
welfare undertakings.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fangyu, in the township of Guoshuiping, made donations to
build a TV relay station, in addition to schools and roads. Also,
he had a ruined river embankment rebuilt last year at a cost of
20,000 yuan. 
</P>
