"Exports, an important voice for the Italian economy, must be
paid the attention they deserve, including fiscal measures for
those investing for exports and buying companies in other
countries," Fantozzi told a round-table discussion held on the
future of small and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that tax breaks for investing abroad and
exports does not mean taking work away from the country. "On the
contrary, it guarantees more," he said.
</P>
<P>
Exportation is important for Italy's gold industry as it offers
115,000 jobs and generates an annual turnover of some 20 trillion
lire (1.186 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Present at Sunday's discussion was Antonio Zucchi, president of
the Arezzo Industrialists Association, who criticized that tax
penalties imposed on exporting companies and insufficient
coordination between all agencies designed to support exports are
hindering the internationalization of Italian economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans to Stop Using Leaded Petrol by 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided that leaded petrol will no longer be used in the country
by 1999, as part of the national effort to reduce air pollution
emitted by motor vehicles, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Mines and Energy Ida Bagus Sujana said here on
Sunday that leaded petrol will be gradually phased out and
replaced by unleaded petrol, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The state oil and gas company has already begun to produce and
sell unleaded petrol, but the more environment-friendly fuel is
yet to prove popular with motorists, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The government is also trying to promote the use of compressed
natural gas (CNG) or liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) as an
alternative fuel to petrol.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the number of motor vehicles in
Indonesia is increasing at an average rate of 12 percent a year.
In 1995 the total number of registered motor vehicles in the
country stood at 12,833,536, of which 25 percent were operating in
the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta administration has forged a cooperation agreement
with the Association of National Oil and Gas Companies to
construct a total of 21 automotive gas filling stations in the
city over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of the "blue sky" program launched by the
city administration a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
A research conducted recently by an environment enforcement
board showed that the level of pollution in big cities especially
Jakarta has reached some 1,200 tons monthly, and anxiously 67
percent of air pollution is caused by transportation activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
