<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Agree to U.N. Police Deployed in Brcko </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Serbs on Sunday
agreed to the deployment of a 200-member U.N. police contingent in
the disputed town of Brcko.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced by Bosnian Serb Interior Minister
Dragan Kijac after he discussed the matter with Manfred Zeiner,
chief of the International Police Task Force.
</P>
<P>
Kijac also said that the Bosnian Serbs will strive to maintain
the stability of Brcko, claimed by Serbs, Croats and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Controlled by the Serbs since May 1992, Brcko is claimed by the
Croats and Muslims who were in a majority in the town before the
war.
</P>
<P>
The disputed town is still the subject of an international
arbitration which decided to allow the Serbs to continue to
administer the town until March next year when a final decision on
its future is taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
