<HEADLINE> Thailand Initiates Course Swaps Among Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is planning to introduce
a policy to allow college students to take courses among various
universities as a bid to ease the shortage of lecturers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Thai University Affairs Ministry is consulting with
university rectors on the initiative, which means the transfer of
credits among universities will be facilitated.
</P>
<P>
Wanchai Sirichana, permanent secretary of the ministry, said
that most universities in Thailand have similar standards of
education and they are able to provide suitable teaching.
</P>
<P>
According to the initiative, students will be allowed to
register for subjects at other universities and then have the
credits transferred to their own universities.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is expected to come into practice in the next
academic year if it wins the support from university rectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
