<HEADLINE> 114 Philippine Cops, Soldiers Tagged in Kidnaps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- At least 114 national policemen
and government soldiers have been involved in the recent rash of
kidnapping in the Philippines, the Philippine Daily Inquirer said
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Benjamin Libarnes, head of the Presidential
Task Force on Intelligence and Counter-Intelligence, as saying
that 87 policemen and 27 soldiers were part of kidnapping
syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The 114 members of the Philippine National Police and the Armed
Forces were among 652 persons that intelligence agencies had
monitored for their involvement in kidnapping, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Libarnes confirmed the existence of 83 kidnap
syndicates nationwide, 43 of which operate in Manila and nearby
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted informed sources as saying that the
figure did not include former policemen and soldiers, as well as
those involved in bank robbery, car theft and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks, at least five kidnapping cases were
reported.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 241 people were abducted in the country, prompting
the Fortune magazine to call the Philippines the "kidnapping
capital of Asia" in its March 17 issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
