<HEADLINE> Chang Upset, Hingis Marches on at Lipton Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Third seed Michael Chang saw
his winning streak halted by Sergi Bruguera in the third round of
the Lipton Championships Sunday, but women's top seed Martina
Hingis showed no sign that her victorious run would end any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
A sluggish looking Chang fell 6-4, 6-3 to the 35th-ranked
Spaniard in a clash of former French Open champions, ending the
American's string of 11 consecutive match wins.
</P>
<P>
Chang, who won Lipton in 1992, had claimed titles in his
previous two tour events at Memphis and Indian Wells.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, meanwhile, stretch her perfect 1997 match record to
22-0 by taking out a player who has been projected as one of the
Swiss teen's likely future challengers.
</P>
<P>
In a third-round matchup of 16-year-olds, soon-to-be world
number one Hingis bumped out American Venus Williams 6-4, 6-2
after Williams opened the match strongly with two early service
breaks for a 3-0 first-set lead.
</P>
<P>
In other men's plays, swift-serving Australian Mark
Philippoussis dominated ninth-seed Wayne Ferreira of South Africa
6-3, 6-3 in another third round match, while Andrei Medvedev of
Ukraine bounced 11th seed Alberto Costa of Spain 6-3, 3-6, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
At 30-0 in the second game of the second set, Philippoussis
produced a serve that was clocked at 141 mph (227 kph), extremely
close to his ATP Tour record 142 mile per hour (228 kph) .
</P>
<P>
In women's event, young stars continued shining when promising
15-year-old Russian Anna Kournikova recovered from a first-set
drubbing to oust 34th-ranked Katarina Studenikova of Slovakia 1-6,
6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Second seed Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, third seed Jana Novotna
and fourth seed Monica Seles, playing her first tournament of the
year, also sailed further in the tournament. 
</P>
