<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenyang Fights against Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, capital of northeast
China's Liaoning Province, has taken a move to rein in discharges
of wastes from local industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The city is one of the well-known industrial bases of China,
but the deterioration of the local environment in recent years has
endangered the health and normal life of local people.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that local environmental protection units
have set up warning signs that can be easily seen at the locations
of 1,000 sources of wastes, including the 408 enterprises that
pipe out about 65 percent of the waste water, gas, and residue of
the city every year.
</P>
<P>
The 50 outlets generating toxic waste have larger signs, with
black characters written on yellow board.
</P>
<P>
The signs helped arouse the public's concern over pollution,
and gave them better a understanding of what the environment meant
to their lives, according to local observers.
</P>
<P>
An old worker in a Shenyang-based transformer plant said that
he did not know that his plant was generating wastes harmful to
him and his colleagues until he saw the signs.
</P>
<P>
The environmental protection units will create a computer
archive for each of the waste outlets, and conduct regular tests
of the outlets for data on the discharged wastes.
</P>
<P>
Places generating intense noise also have signs erected to warn
workers at these businesses and people in the neighborhood of
noise pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
