<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Leaders Highlight Issues Confronting Muslim World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Various leaders attending the
special summit of the Organization of Islamic Conference have
called for coordinated efforts to resolve the issues confronting
the Muslim world peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The leaders during their short statements made here on Sunday
at the working session of the OIC special summit touched upon
issues including Middle East, Kashmir, Afghanistan, terrorism,
narcotics, development and other economic issues.
</P>
<P>
President of Tajikistan Emomali Rakhmonov urged the Islamic
world to devise ways to protect the sovereignty and independence
of the member states.
</P>
<P>
He called for a peaceful solution of the Afghan crisis, saying
that the OIC had yet not utilize all the possibilities to resolve
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Emomali said Pakistan and Iran could play an important role in
its settlement.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to combat the illegal production and
trafficking of narcotics, saying that if the OIC, central Asian
states enter into a regional cooperation, this problem could be
tackled to a great extent.
</P>
<P>
Gambian President Yahya Hammeh said Islam was the religion of
peace.
</P>
<P>
He said that greater solidarity and more cooperation were
required to address the critical economic problems facing the
Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
It was the moral obligation of the Muslim countries to extend
support to the less fortunate members, the Gambian president
added.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese President Omer Hassan emphasized the need for taking
joint steps for ensuring food security and adoption of modern
technology in various fields to achieve the desired results.
</P>
<P>
President of the Maldives Maumoon Abdul Gayoon expressed his
profound concern on the continued tension between India and
Pakistan over Kashmir and appreciated the recent steps taken for
finding a peaceful settlement of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the recent actions by Israel to build Jewish
settlement in Jerusalem, saying it could jeopardize the peace
process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Vice President of Syria Abdul Haleem Khaddam said his country
would always remember the position taken by Pakistan on the Middle
East issue.
</P>
<P>
He said Israeli actions would undermine the peace process in
the Middle East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
