<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamabad Declaration for Broadening Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Extraordinary Summit of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) has adopted a 25-point
"Islamabad Declaration" to broaden cooperation among OIC members
States in all spheres.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was adopted here on Sunday night at the end of
the one-day OIC special summit in commemorating the 50th
anniversary of independence of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said that comprehensive peace in the Middle
East could not be achieved without the implementation of the UN
Security Council resolutions 242, 338 and 425 as well as the
principles of "land for peace".
</P>
<P>
The UN resolutions guarantee Israel's total withdrawal from all
occupied Palestinian and Arab territories to the lines of June 4,
1967 including the city of Al-Quds Al-Sharif, the Syrian Golan as
well as occupied South Lebanon and Western Bekaa, occupied since
March 14, 1978.
</P>
<P>
It called upon Israel to reaffirm its adherence to the
commitments, agreements and undertakings given by it during the
negotiations and to resume the talks on the Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
The OIC member states upheld the fundamental human rights of
the people of Kashmir and the exercise of the right to
self-determination in accordance with the relevant UN resolutions
and condemn the massive violations of their human rights.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed that any political process/election under
foreign occupation cannot be a substitute to the exercise of the
right of self-determination by the people of Jammu and Kashmir,
</P>
<P>
They observed that a substantive dialogue is essential to
resolve the Kashmir dispute which is the basic cause of tension
between India and Pakistan and support the efforts of the Pakistan
government to achieve a just and peaceful solution of the Jammu
and Kashmir dispute and call upon the government of India to
respond positively.
</P>
<P>
The OIC member states reaffirmed the need to preserve the
national unity, sovereignty, independence, territorial integrity
and Islamic character of Afghanistan and in this respect
emphasized the principles of non-intervention and non-interference
and call upon all states to end immediately the supply of arms and
ammunition to all Afghan parties.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated the need for early political reconciliation in
Afghanistan and supported the efforts of OIC and United Nations in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
It was also imperative that the international community
provides adequate assistance for rehabilitation and reconstruction
in Afghanistan including for the repatriation of Afghan refugees,
the declaration said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
