<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment in Poor Countries Reaches Record Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Private foreign investment in
developing countries surged at a record rate last year, but
official aid from governments declined sharply, the World Bank
said in a report today.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report said that private investment in poor
countries jumped by 60 billion U.S. dollars last year to a record
244 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Much of the private investment capital is going to build the
infrastructures of the recipient countries, particularly in
communications, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Investment in China rose by 7 billion to 42 billion dollars.
Significant advances also occurred elsewhere in Asia, notably in
Indonesia and Thailand, and in Brazil and Argentina in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, private capital flows remained modest but are 10
times greater than they were at the start of the 1990s, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"The growth of private capital flows should continue (in 1997),
as more developing countries improve (economic) management and
open their markets to competition," said James Stiglitz, the
World Bank's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report also said that official foreign aid fell
by 1 billion U.S. dollars last year, back to 1990 levels.
</P>
<P>
It said that U.S. foreign aid totaled about 12.5 billion
dollars in the fiscal year of 1996, down almost 9 percent from the
previous year's 13.7 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
