<HEADLINE> SDA Official Denies Plan To Divide Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Party
of Democratic Action (SDA) denied the report that the Bosnian
Muslim leaders were preparing for a tacit division of Bosnia,
according to a press report on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Sarajevo Daily Oslobodjenje in its report quoted SDA vice
president Edhem Bicakcic as saying that the party would keep
fighting for an integrated and democratic Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"Our only option is an integrated and single Bosnia," said
Bicakcic, who is also prime minister of the Bosnian Federation.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the non-implementation of the Dayton peace
accords could result in Muslims accepting Bosnia's division, with
its borders being redrawn with a new war.
</P>
<P>
Bicakcic's remarks were in response to press reports about
Muslim leadership's readiness to accept division of Bosnia
according to ethnic lines.
</P>
<P>
A recent public opinion survey showed that 22 percent of Muslim
favored a separate single-nation state.
</P>
<P>
Slobodna Bosnia, a weekly, reported that there were even
private discussions among officials of three ethnic nations on
territorial exchanges in order to facilitate the division of
Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970324.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Chances, Challenges for OAU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Chances and challenges loom over
the Wednesday Lome summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) on ending the exploding Zaire crisis which has shocked the
whole continent.
</P>
<P>
As the crisis could cause huge bloodshed, mass migration, arms
proliferation and unrest in central Africa, the special summit is
catching much more attention not only from African countries but
from the rest of the international community.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, OAU Chief Salim Ahmed Salim
and about 30 heads of state in Africa or their representatives
will attend the summit focusing on how to pursue an immediate
cease-fire, negotiations and elections in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of a peace-keeping force in Zaire may be
discussed at the summit trying to broker peace between the
warring sides in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Several signals indicate that the summit might produce some
positive results and thus bring a ray of hope to a negotiated
settlement of the bloodshed. Chances do exist.
</P>
<P>
First, to end conflicts, African countries generally stand for
seeking common ground while reserving differences, saying they
are willing to join efforts in bringing about reconciliation
between the warring sides.
</P>
<P>
They also agree that the national sovereignty and territorial
integrity of Zaire should be safeguarded and maintained.
</P>
<P>
Second, the Lome summit will be held on the basis of three
Nairobi summits on the Zairean war and the mediation efforts by
South African President Nelson Mandela to explore the
possibilities of direct dialogue between the Zairean government
and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the host country of Togo, along with other African
countries, claimed they have confidence and determination to deal
with the deteriorating situation in Zaire with their own wisdom
and abilities.
</P>
<P>
The African countries have accumulated some successful
experiences in the process of resolving conflicts in the
continent, for example, in Sierra Leone, Liberia and the Central
African Republic.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, both President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader
Laurent Kabila have a desire for a peaceful solution to the
crisis. The Zairean government has accepted the U.N. five-point
peace plan and Mobutu is calling for an immediate cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Despite victories in the battlefield, Kabila has stated that
talks are "important." He insists on direct negotiations with
Mobutu and opposes to seceding Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the United States and France, two major players
among western powers in the Zaire crisis, have coordinated their
positions on the issue and called for "an immediate truce and
negotiations" between the warring parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Chief Annan said during his earlier visit to South Africa
that he is optimistic that the Lome summit would put Zaire on the
road to peace.
</P>
<P>
However, there poise serious obstacles which might thwart the
peace efforts by African countries and the U.N. Challenges seem
bigger.
</P>
<P>
The development in Zaire is unpredictable and situation there
seems worsening. Up to now, it is hard to achieve cease-fire as
rebel leader Kabila sticks to talks before a truce.
</P>
<P>
Since rising in revolt in eastern Zaire last October, the
Tutsi-dominated rebels have seized one third of the country,
including the third largest city Kisangani, and vowed to press on
to take Zaire's capital Kinshasa in June.
</P>
<P>
No truce before negotiations, no end to fighting before
Zairean President Mobutu steps down, Kabila said time and again
and his troops are advancing toward Zaire's second largest city
Lubumbashi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zairean government army argued that they lost
only battles, not wars, and an ailing Mobutu returned to Kinshasa
from France Friday in attempts to reverse the situation.
</P>
<P>
The government troops will "continue to fight" against the
rebels, Chief of the General Staff of the army Lieko Bokungu
declared.
</P>
<P>
And before a cease-fire is realized, it is too early to mention
the deployment of a peace-keeping force in Zaire and it is also
not easy to raise funds to keep up such a force.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the rebels have refused to accept intervention by
sending such a force to Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Just as OAU chief Salim put it in an interview with Xinhua on
Saturday that how to make the two warring sides accept a
cease-fire unconditionally is "one of the challenges facing the
summit," maybe the biggest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
